{"title":"msn-srvr-container_platform","id":"f4462a22-e160-4411-ae83-c08656cb2c90","stigs":[{"stig_name":"Container Platform Security Requirements Guide","display_name":"Container Platform Security Requirements Guide","stig_id":"Container_Platform_SRG","release_info":"Release: 3 Benchmark Date: 02 Jul 2025","version":"2","uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","reference_identifier":"5239","size":187,"rules":[{"group_id_src":"V-233015","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233015","title":"SRG-APP-000014","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233015","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use TLS 1.2 or greater for secure container image transport from trusted sources.","rule_id_src":"SV-233015r960759_rule","rule_id":"SV-233015r960759","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000014-CTR-000035","rule_title":"The container platform must use TLS 1.2 or greater for secure container image transport from trusted sources.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use TLS 1.2 or greater when components communicate internally or externally. The fix ensures that all communication components in the container platform are configured to utilize secure versions of TLS.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to verify that TLS 1.2 or greater is being used for secure container image transport from trusted sources. \n\nIf TLS 1.2 or greater is not being used for secure container image transport, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The authenticity and integrity of the container image during the container image lifecycle is part of the overall security posture of the container platform. This begins with the container image creation and pull of a base image from a trusted source for child container image creation and the instantiation of the new image into a running service. If an insecure protocol is used during transmission of container images at any step of the lifecycle, a bad actor may inject nefarious code into the container image. The container image, when instantiated, then becomes a security risk to the container platform, the host server, and other containers within the container platform. To thwart the injection of code during transmission, a secure protocol (TLS 1.2 or newer) must be used. Further guidance on secure transport protocols can be found in NIST SP 800-52.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000068"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"85d67e05-ee64-423c-ae7a-a7a9d6642b3d","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman uses the host system’s RHEL 9 OpenSSL libraries and certificate trust store for all registry communications, which automatically enforce secure transport using TLS 1.2 or newer (TLS 1.3 in current RHEL 9 releases).\nWhen images are pulled from trusted registries (e.g., registry.redhat.io or internal GitLab), connections occur strictly over HTTPS with validated server certificates, and insecure HTTP registries are rejected unless explicitly configured.\nSince Podman inherits OS‑level FIPS‑validated cryptographic modules and defaults to secure protocols, image transport meets the requirement for TLS 1.2 or greater."},{"group_id_src":"V-233016","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233016","title":"SRG-APP-000014","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233016","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use TLS 1.2 or greater for secure communication.","rule_id_src":"SV-233016r960759_rule","rule_id":"SV-233016r960759","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000014-CTR-000040","rule_title":"The container platform must use TLS 1.2 or greater for secure communication.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use TLS 1.2 or greater for node and component communication.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to verify that TLS 1.2 or greater is being used for communication by the container platform nodes and components. \n\nIf TLS 1.2 or greater is not being used for secure communication, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The authenticity and integrity of the container platform and communication between nodes and components must be secure. If an insecure protocol is used during transmission of data, the data can be intercepted and manipulated. The manipulation of data can be used to inject status changes of the container platform, causing the execution of containers or reporting an incorrect healthcheck. To thwart the manipulation of the data during transmission, a secure protocol (TLS 1.2 or newer) must be used. Further guidance on secure transport protocols can be found in NIST SP 800-52.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000068"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4ac68250-a388-4a6a-9dc4-2422998ae80d","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"host is already set to use fips and tls > 1.2","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not include or manage internal node‑to‑node or component communication channels.\nAny network communications (such as image pulls or registry interactions) are handled over HTTPS (TLS 1.2 or newer) using the system’s OpenSSL and certificate trust store.\nThe RHEL 9 host enforces FIPS‑validated cryptographic libraries, ensuring all TLS operations use approved algorithms and protocols (TLS 1.2 or greater).\nBecause all external communication occurs through secure, OS‑controlled TLS libraries, this requirement is satisfied."},{"group_id_src":"V-233019","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233019","title":"SRG-APP-000023","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233019","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use a centralized user management solution to support account management functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233019r1043176_rule","rule_id":"SV-233019r1043176","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000023-CTR-000055","rule_title":"The container platform must use a centralized user management solution to support account management functions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use a centralized user management system for user management functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if it is using a centralized user management system for user management functions. \n\nIf the container platform is not using a centralized user management system for user management functions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Enterprise environments make application account management challenging and complex. A manual process for account management functions adds the risk of a potential oversight or other error.\n\nA comprehensive application account management process that includes automation helps to ensure accounts designated as requiring attention are consistently and promptly addressed. Examples include, but are not limited to, using automation to take action on multiple accounts designated as inactive, suspended, or terminated or by disabling accounts located in non-centralized account stores, such as multiple servers. This requirement applies to all account types, including individual/user, shared, group, system, guest/anonymous, emergency, developer/manufacturer/vendor, temporary, and service.\n\nThe application must be configured to automatically provide account management functions, and these functions must immediately enforce the organization's current account policy. The automated mechanisms may reside within the application itself or may be offered by the operating system or other infrastructure-providing automated account management capabilities. Automated mechanisms may be comprised of differing technologies, that when placed together, contain an overall automated mechanism supporting an organization's automated account management requirements.\n\nAccount management functions include: assignment of group or role membership; identifying account type; specifying user access authorizations (i.e., privileges); account removal, update, or termination; and administrative alerts. The use of automated mechanisms can include: using email or text messaging to automatically notify account managers when users are terminated or transferred; using the information system to monitor account usage; or using automated telephonic notification to report atypical system account usage.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4c9facc5-fb15-4fde-ac26-a2d2374c0e4c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman uses the hosts authentication mechanics. The host is joined to active directory for user managment."},{"group_id_src":"V-233020","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233020","title":"SRG-APP-000024","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233020","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically remove or disable temporary user accounts after 72 hours.","rule_id_src":"SV-233020r960771_rule","rule_id":"SV-233020r960771","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000024-CTR-000060","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically remove or disable temporary user accounts after 72 hours.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically remove or disable temporary user accounts after 72 hours.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if temporary user accounts are automatically removed or disabled after 72 hours. \n\nIf temporary user accounts are not automatically removed or disabled after 72 hours, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If temporary user accounts remain active when no longer needed or for an excessive period, these accounts may be used to gain unauthorized access. To mitigate this risk, automated termination of all temporary user accounts must be set upon account creation.\n\nTemporary user accounts are established as part of normal account activation procedures when there is a need for short-term accounts without the demand for immediacy in account activation.\n\nIf temporary user accounts are used, the application must be configured to automatically terminate these types of accounts after a DoD-defined period of 72 hours.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000016"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"196a94eb-186b-4a1e-911b-657fcf63da27","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage or maintain user accounts and has no capability to create or control temporary accounts.\nUser authentication and account lifecycle management are handled entirely by the RHEL 9 operating system or the organization’s upstream identity provider (e.g., SSSD, LDAP, or Active Directory).\nBecause Podman relies on host user accounts and has no internal mechanism to create, disable, or remove temporary accounts, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233021","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233021","title":"SRG-APP-000025","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233021","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically disable accounts after a 35-day period of account inactivity.","rule_id_src":"SV-233021r960774_rule","rule_id":"SV-233021r960774","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000025-CTR-000065","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically disable accounts after a 35-day period of account inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically disable accounts after a 35-day period of account inactivity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the container platform automatically disables accounts after a 35-day period of account inactivity. \r\n\r\nIf the container platform does not automatically disable accounts after a 35-day period of account inactivity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Attackers that are able to exploit an inactive account can potentially obtain and maintain undetected access to an application. Owners of inactive accounts will not notice if unauthorized access to their user account has been obtained. Applications need to track periods of user inactivity and disable accounts after 35 days of inactivity. Such a process greatly reduces the risk that accounts will be hijacked, leading to a data compromise.\r\n\r\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.\r\n\r\nThis policy does not apply to either emergency accounts or infrequently used accounts. Infrequently used accounts are local login administrator accounts used by system administrators when network or normal logon/access is not available. Emergency accounts are administrator accounts created in response to crisis situations.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000017"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c7f899ee-1794-47fd-856d-7a4c81b4b29f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user accounts or authentication and therefore does not have the capability to track or disable inactive accounts.\nUser account control, including automatic disabling after periods of inactivity, is handled entirely by the RHEL 9 host operating system using /etc/login.defs or /etc/default/useradd parameters (e.g., INACTIVE=35) or directory‑service policies when integrated with enterprise authentication.\nSince Podman does not implement local accounts or authentication mechanisms, this control is not applicable to the container runtime"},{"group_id_src":"V-233022","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233022","title":"SRG-APP-000026","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233022","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account creation.","rule_id_src":"SV-233022r960777_rule","rule_id":"SV-233022r960777","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000026-CTR-000070","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account creation.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically create audit records on account creation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if audit records are automatically created upon account creation. \n\nIf audit records are not automatically created upon account creation, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of re-establishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to create a new account. Auditing of account creation is one method for mitigating this risk. A comprehensive account management process will ensure an audit trail documents the creation of application user accounts and, as required, notifies administrators and/or application when accounts are created. Such a process greatly reduces the risk that accounts will be surreptitiously created, and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000018"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7d26d113-1c23-420a-abf8-832709650e31","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not maintain or manage internal user accounts; it relies entirely on the underlying RHEL 9 operating system for authentication and account management.\nUser account creation on the host is automatically audited by the auditd service through rules monitoring /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group.\nBecause Podman has no account database or account‑creation functionality of its own, this control is not applicable to the container runtime"},{"group_id_src":"V-233023","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233023","title":"SRG-APP-000027","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233023","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-233023r960780_rule","rule_id":"SV-233023r960780","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000027-CTR-000075","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account modification.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically audit account modification.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if account modification is automatically audited. \n\nIf account modification is not automatically audited, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to a system, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of re-establishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to modify an existing account. Auditing of account creation is one method for mitigating this risk. A comprehensive account management process will ensure an audit trail documents the creation of application user accounts and, as required, notifies administrators and/or application when accounts are created. Such a process greatly reduces the risk that accounts will be surreptitiously created and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001403"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"73a56113-d162-4d3e-b831-3bff2200479b","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not maintain internal user accounts or perform user management functions.\nAll user and group accounts, as well as account modifications, are managed and automatically audited by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system through auditd.\nBecause there are no Podman‑specific accounts or account modification capabilities, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233024","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233024","title":"SRG-APP-000028","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233024","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account-disabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233024r960783_rule","rule_id":"SV-233024r960783","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000028-CTR-000080","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account-disabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically audit account disabling.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if account disabling is automatically audited. \n\nIf account disabling is not automatically audited, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When application accounts are disabled, user accessibility is affected. Once an attacker establishes access to an application, the attacker often attempts to disable authorized accounts to disrupt services or prevent the implementation of countermeasures. Auditing account-disabling actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/audit mechanisms meeting or exceeding access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001404"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c5ce8292-8e93-4d58-aca4-ce621f9bec75","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user accounts; all user management activities, including account disabling actions, are handled by the RHEL 9 host’s account and authentication mechanisms.\nThe system’s auditd service automatically audits all changes to /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group, capturing user account lock, unlock, and disable events through rules such as -w /etc/shadow -p wa -k identity.\nBecause Podman inherits host authentication controls and the host’s audit configuration already records these events, this requirement is satisfied at the system level."},{"group_id_src":"V-233025","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233025","title":"SRG-APP-000029","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233025","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account removal actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233025r960786_rule","rule_id":"SV-233025r960786","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000029-CTR-000085","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account removal actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically audit account removal.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if account removal is automatically audited. \n\nIf account removal is not automatically audited, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When application accounts are removed, user accessibility is affected. Once an attacker establishes access to an application, the attacker often attempts to remove authorized accounts to disrupt services or prevent the implementation of countermeasures. Auditing account removal actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/audit mechanisms meeting or exceeding access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001405"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a5a565bf-dc47-422d-acce-1ff920b84c8e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not maintain or manage application‑level user accounts; all user and group accounts exist on the underlying RHEL 9 host.\nAccount creation, modification, and removal actions are automatically audited by the system’s auditd service through existing rules monitoring /etc/passwd, /etc/shadow, and /etc/group.\nEntries in audit.rules such as -w /etc/passwd -p wa -k identity ensure any account removal is logged with responsible user, timestamp, and outcome.\nBecause account management and auditing occur at the host level and include all users capable of running Podman, this requirement is satisfied"},{"group_id_src":"V-233026","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233026","title":"SRG-APP-000033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233026","severity":"medium","group_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform registry.","rule_id_src":"SV-233026r960792_rule","rule_id":"SV-233026r960792","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000033-CTR-000090","rule_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform registry.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use least privilege and need to know when granting access to the container platform registry. The fix ensures the proper roles and permissions are configured.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if least privilege and need-to-know access is being used for container platform registry access. \n\nIf least privilege and need-to-know access is not being used for container platform registry access, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform registry is used to store images and is the keeper of truth for trusted images within the platform. To guarantee the images integrity, access to the registry must be limited to those individuals who need to perform tasks to the images such as the update, creation, or deletion of images. Without this control access, images can be deleted that are in use by the container platform causing a denial of service (DoS), and images can be modified or introduced without going through the testing and validation process allowing for the intentional or unintentional introduction of containers with flaws and vulnerabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b3b29518-1125-473c-9fb8-24eaafccbb34","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not include or manage an internal container registry.\nImage storage and access are handled through external registries such as Red Hat’s registry.redhat.io or an organizational GitLab instance, both of which maintain their own authentication and role‑based access controls.\nBecause the Podman runtime only pulls or pushes images to these external registries and does not manage registry permissions, this requirement is not applicable to the container platform itself."},{"group_id_src":"V-233027","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233027","title":"SRG-APP-000033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233027","severity":"medium","group_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform runtime.","rule_id_src":"SV-233027r960792_rule","rule_id":"SV-233027r960792","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000033-CTR-000095","rule_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform runtime.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use least privilege and need to know when granting access to the container runtime. The fix ensures the proper roles and permissions are configured.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if only those individuals with runtime duties have access to the container platform runtime. \n\nIf users have access to the container platform runtime that do not have runtime duties, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform runtime is used to instantiate containers. If this process is accessed by those persons who are not authorized, those containers offering services can be brought to a denial of service (DoS) situation, disabling a large number of services with a small change to the container platform. To limit this threat, it is important to limit access to the runtime to only those individuals with runtime duties.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a650b431-1a47-4b3d-a8aa-f17c3b789dae","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman is operated only by non‑privileged (rootless) users and does not run a shared or multi‑tenant container runtime service.\nEach user executes containers within their own process and namespace, fully isolated from other users and without elevated privileges.\nAccess to Podman binaries is controlled through standard Linux file permissions, and only authorized administrators may install or modify runtime components.\nBecause the container runtime is limited to rootless operations and there are no separate runtime roles or elevated access requirements, this control is not applicable to the current Podman configuration."},{"group_id_src":"V-233028","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233028","title":"SRG-APP-000033","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233028","severity":"medium","group_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform keystore.","rule_id_src":"SV-233028r960792_rule","rule_id":"SV-233028r960792","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000033-CTR-000100","rule_title":"Least privilege access and need to know must be required to access the container platform keystore.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use least privilege and need to know when granting access to the container keystore. The fix ensures the proper roles and permissions are configured.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if only those individuals with keystore duties have access to the container platform keystore. \n\nIf users have access to the container platform keystore that do not have keystore duties, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform keystore is used to store access keys and tokens for trusted access to and from the container platform. The keystore gives the container platform a method to store the confidential data in a secure way and to encrypt the data when at rest. If this data is not protected through access controls, it can be used to access trusted sources as the container platform breaking the trusted relationship. To circumvent unauthorized access to the keystore, the container platform must have access controls in place to only allow those individuals with keystore duties.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000213"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"105e635e-1cf8-4bcc-ab5b-595565921290","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not provide or manage a dedicated container platform keystore.\nIt relies on the underlying RHEL 9 host for secure storage and protection of any credentials, using system‑level mechanisms such as the kernel keyring and system certificate store.\nBecause there is no Podman‑specific keystore and access controls are enforced by host file system permissions and user privileges, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233029","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233029","title":"SRG-APP-000038","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233029","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information within the container platform based on organization-defined information flow control policies.","rule_id_src":"SV-233029r960801_rule","rule_id":"SV-233029r960801","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000038-CTR-000105","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information within the container platform based on organization-defined information flow control policies.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information within the container platform based on organization-defined information flow control policies.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information within the container platform based on organization-defined information flow control policies is being enforced. \n\nIf the organization-defined information flow policies are not being enforced, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling information flow between the container platform components and container user services instantiated by the container platform must enforce organization-defined information flow policies. Example methods for information flow control are using labels and separate namespace for containers to segregate services; user permissions and roles to limit what user services are available to each user; controlling the user the services are able to execute as; and limiting inter-container network traffic and the resources containers can consume.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001368"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"8cc44c6f-3733-42f3-b130-f1f3afa3a15b","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe Podman runtime operates entirely under non‑privileged (rootless) user contexts, with each container isolated in its own user and network namespace.\nThis configuration provides natural separation of processes and data without central management of information flow policies.\nBecause the environment is not interconnected with other container platforms or external systems and the organization has not defined specific internal information‑flow control policies, no further enforcement is required.\nAccordingly, this control is not applicable to the current Podman implementation."},{"group_id_src":"V-233030","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233030","title":"SRG-APP-000039","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233030","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information between interconnected systems and services based on organization-defined information flow control policies.","rule_id_src":"SV-233030r960804_rule","rule_id":"SV-233030r960804","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000039-CTR-000110","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce approved authorizations for controlling the flow of information between interconnected systems and services based on organization-defined information flow control policies.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to implement organization-defined information flow controls.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if organization-defined information flow controls are implemented. \n\nIf information flow controls are not implemented, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling information flow between the container platform components and container user services instantiated by the container platform must enforce organization-defined information flow policies. Example methods for information flow control are: using labels for containers to segregate services; user permissions and roles to limit what user services are available to each user; controlling the user the services are able to execute as; and limiting inter-container network traffic and the resources containers can consume.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001414"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"240e7e1e-c490-4ce0-998e-4918cd77b180","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe Podman container runtime operates exclusively under a non‑privileged user context and is not interconnected with other container platforms or external systems.\nThere are no organization‑defined information flow control policies applicable to this deployment, and containers do not exchange data across systems that would require such enforcement.\nBecause the environment is isolated, uses rootless containers, and does not participate in inter‑platform communication, this requirement is not applicable to the current Podman implementation.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233031","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233031","title":"SRG-APP-000065","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233031","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15-minute time period.","rule_id_src":"SV-233031r960840_rule","rule_id":"SV-233031r960840","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000065-CTR-000115","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15-minute time period.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15-minute time period.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if it is configured to enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15-minute time period.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to enforce the limit of three consecutive invalid logon attempts by a user during a 15-minute time period, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed login attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000044"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"1f7491ef-b50e-4cb9-822b-65af9ecf9fa1","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not provide or manage its own account authentication; it relies entirely on the underlying RHEL 9 host for user login and privilege enforcement.\nThe host implements account lockout controls through /etc/security/faillock.conf, which enforces a maximum of three consecutive invalid logon attempts within a 15‑minute period by default when deny=3 and fail_interval=900 are set.\nBecause Podman access is tied to host user authentication, this control is satisfied at the operating‑system level."},{"group_id_src":"V-233032","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233032","title":"SRG-APP-000068","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233032","severity":"low","group_title":"The container platform must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to platform components.","rule_id_src":"SV-233032r960843_rule","rule_id":"SV-233032r960843","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000068-CTR-000120","rule_title":"The container platform must display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to platform components.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to display the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner before granting access to container platform components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner is configured to be displayed before granting access to platform components. \n\nLog in to the container platform components and verify that the Standard Mandatory DoD  Notice and Consent Banner is being displayed before granting access.\n\nIf the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner is not configured or is not displayed before granting access to container platform components, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform has countless components where different access levels are needed. To control access, the user must first log in to the component and then be presented with a DoD-approved use notification banner before granting access to the component. This guarantees privacy and security notification verbiage used is consistent with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, standards, and guidance.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000048"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"6088bbe9-5593-49c6-91b1-0dc08e5409d5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthe standard banner is displayed on ssh access to the host system. this is not specific to podman, since podman is a cli command and not something that is logged into or out of"},{"group_id_src":"V-233033","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233033","title":"SRG-APP-000069","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233033","severity":"low","group_title":"The container platform must retain the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner on the screen until users acknowledge the usage and conditions and take explicit actions to log on for further access.","rule_id_src":"SV-233033r960846_rule","rule_id":"SV-233033r960846","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000069-CTR-000125","rule_title":"The container platform must retain the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner on the screen until users acknowledge the usage and conditions and take explicit actions to log on for further access.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to retain the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner on the screen until users acknowledge the usage and conditions and take explicit actions to log on for further access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Log in to the container platform components to determine if the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner remains on the screen until users acknowledge the usage and conditions and take explicit actions to log on for further access. \n\nIf the Standard Mandatory DoD Notice and Consent Banner does not stay on the screen until the users acknowledge the usage and conditions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The banner must be acknowledged by the user prior to allowing the user access to any container platform component. This provides assurance that the user has seen the message and accepted the conditions for access. If the consent banner is not acknowledged by the user, DoD will not be in compliance with system use notifications required by law. \n\nTo establish acceptance of the application usage policy, a click-through banner at application logon is required. The application must prevent further activity until the user executes a positive action to manifest agreement by clicking on a box indicating \"OK\".","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000050"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"8d4c5662-c392-4b49-9591-dadc33c284f2","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthe standard banner is displayed on ssh access to the host system. this is not specific to podman, since podman is a cli command and not something that is logged into or out of"},{"group_id_src":"V-233038","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233038","title":"SRG-APP-000089","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233038","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records for all DoD-defined auditable events within all components in the platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233038r960879_rule","rule_id":"SV-233038r960879","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000089-CTR-000150","rule_title":"The container platform must generate audit records for all DoD-defined auditable events within all components in the platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records for all DoD-defined auditable events within all the components of the container platform.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to generate audit records for all DoD-defined auditable events within all components in the platform. \n\nGenerate DoD-defined auditable events within all the components to determine if the events are being audited. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to generate audit records for all DoD-defined auditable events within the components or the events are  not generating audit records, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Within the container platform, audit data can be generated from any of the deployed container platform components. This audit data is important when there are issues, including security incidents that must be investigated. To make the audit data worthwhile for the investigation of events, it is necessary to have the appropriate and required data logged. To handle the need to log DoD-defined auditable events, the container platform must offer a mechanism to change and manage the events that are audited.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000169"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"f87b0ffd-111f-45cc-a53e-0e67e4e7a87e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not perform its own auditing; all audit logging is handled by the host RHEL 9 auditd service, which is configured to capture all DoD‑defined auditable events.\nThe existing /etc/audit/audit.rules includes watches for /usr/bin/podman, runc, and crun, recording user identity, command execution, timestamps, and success or failure.\nSince auditd is initialized at system startup and its rule set is immutable (‑e 2), it satisfies the requirement to generate complete audit records for all required security events."},{"group_id_src":"V-233039","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233039","title":"SRG-APP-000090","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233039","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must allow only the ISSM (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","rule_id_src":"SV-233039r960882_rule","rule_id":"SV-233039r960882","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000090-CTR-000155","rule_title":"The container platform must allow only the ISSM (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to only allow the ISSM (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if the container platform is configured to allow only the ISSM (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to only allow the ISSM (or individuals or roles appointed by the ISSM) to select which auditable events are to be audited, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without the capability to restrict which roles and individuals can select which events are audited, unauthorized personnel may be able to prevent the auditing of critical events. Misconfigured audits may degrade the system's performance by overwhelming the audit log. Misconfigured audits may also make it more difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident, or identify those responsible for one.\n \nThe list of audited events is the set of events for which audits are to be generated. This set of events is typically a subset of the list of all events for which the system is capable of generating audit records.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000171"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"eb8729a9-19bf-48f9-8b50-acaf74aa0b10","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not perform its own auditing. All audit events, including container execution and privileged actions, are captured by the RHEL 9 auditd service using rules that watch /usr/bin/podman, runc, and crun. These rules record user identity, command details, and success/failure results. The ruleset is immutable (-e 2) and managed only by authorized administrators, ensuring comprehensive and tamper‑resistant auditing."},{"group_id_src":"V-233040","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233040","title":"SRG-APP-000091","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233040","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access privileges occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-233040r960885_rule","rule_id":"SV-233040r960885","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000091-CTR-000160","rule_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access privileges occur.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts are made to access privileges occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it is configured to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts are made to access privileges. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to generate audit records on successful/unsuccessful access to privileges, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without generating audit records that are specific to the security and mission needs of the organization, it would be difficult to establish, correlate, and investigate the events relating to an incident, or identify those responsible for one.\n\nAudit records can be generated from various components within the information system (e.g., module or policy filter).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3cefb910-d7d6-4854-bad3-398c7fd8f0d1","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not natively generate audit logs; privileged access attempts are logged by the RHEL 9 host’s auditd subsystem.\nAudit rules on /usr/bin/podman and /usr/bin/sudo capture both successful and unsuccessful privilege escalation attempts, including the initiating user and command.\nThis ensures all privilege‑related actions are recorded and traceable through host audit logs."},{"group_id_src":"V-233041","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233041","title":"SRG-APP-000092","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233041","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must initiate session auditing upon startup.","rule_id_src":"SV-233041r960888_rule","rule_id":"SV-233041r960888","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000092-CTR-000165","rule_title":"The container platform must initiate session auditing upon startup.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit logs for session logging at startup. Revise all applicable system documentation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration for session audits. \r\n\r\nEnsure audit policy for session logging at startup is enabled. \r\n\r\nVerify events are written to the log. \r\n\r\nValidate system documentation is current. \r\n\r\nIf the container platform is not configured to meet this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When the container platform is started, container platform components and user services can also be started. It is important that the container platform begin auditing on startup in order to handle container platform startup events along with events for container platform components and services that begin on startup.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001464"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"39775eb9-d0a5-4e95-b429-f7e22730e77b","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman itself does not manage auditing sessions or startup events.\nThe RHEL 9 host’s auditd service and journald are configured to start automatically at system boot, ensuring all Podman container activity is logged as soon as the host initializes.\nBecause auditing begins under host control before any container or Podman process starts, session auditing on startup is effectively enforced."},{"group_id_src":"V-233042","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233042","title":"SRG-APP-000095","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233042","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must identify what type of event has occurred within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233042r960891_rule","rule_id":"SV-233042r960891","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000095-CTR-000170","rule_title":"All audit records must identify what type of event has occurred within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to include the event type in the log data. Revise all applicable system documentation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration for audit event types. Ensure audit policy for event type is enabled. \n\nVerify records showing what type of event occurred are written to the log. \n\nValidate system documentation is current. \n\nIf log data does not show the type of event, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Within the container platform, audit data can be generated from any of the deployed container platform components. This audit data is important when there are issues, such as security incidents, that must be investigated. To make the audit data worthwhile for the investigation of events, it is necessary to know what type of event occurred.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000130"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"f3e8dfcc-1470-4c16-a895-9ac4006f7d05","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman itself does not generate or manage audit logs.\nEvent type information, such as container creation, execution, and removal, is captured and labeled by the host’s auditd and journald services.\nEach record includes the action performed and the associated process or container details, ensuring event types are clearly identified within system audit logs."},{"group_id_src":"V-233043","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233043","title":"SRG-APP-000096","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233043","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform audit records must have a date and time association with all events.","rule_id_src":"SV-233043r960894_rule","rule_id":"SV-233043r960894","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000096-CTR-000175","rule_title":"The container platform audit records must have a date and time association with all events.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to include log date and time with the event. Revise all applicable system documentation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration for audit events date and time. \n\nEnsure audit policy for event date and time are enabled. \n\nVerify records showing event date and time are included in the log. \n\nValidate system documentation is current. \n\nIf the date and time are not included, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Within the container platform, audit data can be generated from any of the deployed container platform components. This audit data is important when there are issues, such as security incidents, that must be investigated. To make the audit data worthwhile for the investigation of events, it is necessary to know when the event occurred. To establish the time of the event, the audit record must contain the date and time.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000131"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7045ff0a-10b0-470f-8249-e4b242a66860","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not perform its own auditing; all event logging and timestamping are managed by the host’s auditd and journald services.\nThese subsystems automatically assign date and time stamps to every event using the system’s synchronized clock (chronyd /NTP).\nAs a result, all container‑related audit records include accurate date and time information"},{"group_id_src":"V-233044","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233044","title":"SRG-APP-000097","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233044","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must identify where in the container platform the event occurred.","rule_id_src":"SV-233044r960897_rule","rule_id":"SV-233044r960897","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000097-CTR-000180","rule_title":"All audit records must identify where in the container platform the event occurred.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records that identify where in the container platform the event occurred.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if all audit records identify where in the container platform the event occurred. \n\nGenerate audit records and view the audit records to verify that the records do identify where in the container platform the event occurred. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to generate audit records that identify where in the container platform the event occurred, or if the generated audit records do not identify where in the container platform the event occurred, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Within the container platform, audit data can be generated from any of the deployed container platform components. This audit data is important when there are issues, such as security incidents, that must be investigated. To make the audit data worthwhile for the investigation of events, it is necessary to know where within the container platform the event occurred.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000132"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"908d8292-57db-4174-85bf-ef05eddd38ba","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman itself does not perform auditing; event collection and logging are handled by the RHEL 9 host’s auditd and journald services.\nThese subsystems capture the container ID, name, and process context in each audit or journal entry, identifying where within the container platform an event occurs.\nThis provides full traceability of container activity through host audit logs"},{"group_id_src":"V-233045","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233045","title":"SRG-APP-000098","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233045","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must identify the source of the event within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233045r960900_rule","rule_id":"SV-233045r960900","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000098-CTR-000185","rule_title":"All audit records must identify the source of the event within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform registry, keystore, and runtime to generate the source of each loggable event. Revise all applicable system documentation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform audit policy configuration for logons establishing the sources of events. \n\nEnsure audit policy is configured to generate sufficient information to resolve the source, e.g., source IP, of the log event. \n\nVerify records showing by requesting a user access the container platform and generate log events, and then review the logs to determine if the source of the event can be established. \n\nIf the source of the event cannot be determined, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Audit data is important when there are issues, to include security incidents that must be investigated. Since the audit data may be part of a larger audit system, it is important for the audit data to also include the container platform name for traceability back to the container platform itself and not just the container platform components.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000133"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"69659ea7-5800-460f-897f-7b926b9b7e42","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not directly perform auditing; all source and origin information for events is captured by the host’s auditd and journald services.\nThese logging components include user identity, host name, and source details (such as TTY or remote IP) for every recorded event.\nThis ensures that each audit record can be traced to its originating source or system, satisfying the requirement."},{"group_id_src":"V-233046","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233046","title":"SRG-APP-000099","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233046","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must generate the event results within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233046r960903_rule","rule_id":"SV-233046r960903","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000099-CTR-000190","rule_title":"All audit records must generate the event results within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records that contain the event result.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if audit records contain the audit event results. \n\nGenerate audit records and review the data to validate that the record does contain the event result. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to generate audit records with  the event result or the audit record does not contain the event result, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Within the container platform, audit data can be generated from any of the deployed container platform components. This audit data is important when there are issues, such as security incidents, that must be investigated. To make the audit data worthwhile for the investigation of events, it is necessary to know the outcome of the event.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000134"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2ff3bef3-aa6a-487f-80f8-0ec65bc361e4","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman itself does not create or manage audit logs; event outcomes and results are recorded by the host’s auditd and journald services.\nThese system audit tools capture whether container or command actions succeed or fail, including the associated return codes.\nThis provides full event result data for container operations within host audit records."},{"group_id_src":"V-233047","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233047","title":"SRG-APP-000100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233047","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must identify any users associated with the event within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233047r960906_rule","rule_id":"SV-233047r960906","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000100-CTR-000195","rule_title":"All audit records must identify any users associated with the event within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform logging system to log the identity of the user or process related to the events.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation and the log files on the application server to determine if the logs contain information that establishes the identity of the user or process associated with log event data. \n\nIf the container platform does not produce logs that establish the identity of the user or process associated with log event data, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without information that establishes the identity of the user associated with the events, security personnel cannot determine responsibility for the potentially harmful event.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c4f2ac51-acf4-4366-8d07-b2011976bae2","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not directly generate audit logs; all user identity information for container actions is recorded by the host’s auditd and journald services.\nThese subsystems capture the executing user’s UID, session context, and command (e.g., podman run) whenever privileged or administrative actions occur.\nThis provides full accountability for container operations through host audit logs rather than Podman itself."},{"group_id_src":"V-233048","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233048","title":"SRG-APP-000100","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233048","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must identify any containers associated with the event within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233048r960906_rule","rule_id":"SV-233048r960906","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000100-CTR-000200","rule_title":"All audit records must identify any containers associated with the event within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to include the component information that generated the audit record.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it is configured to generate audit records that contain the component information that generated the audit record. \n\nGenerate audit records and review the data to determine if records are generated containing the component information that generated the record. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to generate audit records containing the component information or records are generated that do not contain the component information that generated the record, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without information that establishes the identity of the containers offering user services or running on behalf of a user within the platform associated with audit events, security personnel cannot determine responsibility for potentially harmful events.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001487"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"627b9385-775e-4d2e-8d7d-b2f9c3e3a73a","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\n\nPodman does not directly perform auditing or manage audit logs.\nAll audit records, including container start, stop, and execution events, are collected and timestamped by the host’s RHEL 9 auditd and journald services.\nThese system components capture the container identifier and user context for each Podman action, ensuring all relevant container activity is included in host audit records.\nTherefore, auditing controls are fulfilled through the operating system’s audit mechanisms rather than Podman itself.\n\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233049","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233049","title":"SRG-APP-000101","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233049","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records containing the full-text recording of privileged commands or the individual identities of group account users.","rule_id_src":"SV-233049r960909_rule","rule_id":"SV-233049r960909","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000101-CTR-000205","rule_title":"The container platform must generate audit records containing the full-text recording of privileged commands or the individual identities of group account users.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate the full-text recording of privileged commands, or the individual identities of group users, or both.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the documentation and deployment configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to generate full-text recording of privileged commands or the individual identities of group users at a minimum. \n\nHave a user execute a privileged command and review the log data to validate that the full-text or identity of the individual is being logged. \n\nIf the container platform is not meeting this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"During an investigation of an incident, it is important to fully understand what took place. Often, information is not part of the audited event due to the data's nature, security risk, or audit log size. Organizations must consider limiting the additional audit information to only that information explicitly needed for specific audit requirements. At a minimum, the organization must audit either full-text recording of privileged commands, or the individual identities of group users, or both.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000135"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"34fc8e4d-34f1-4823-8014-a321dc9f3177","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman relies on the RHEL 9 host’s auditing system (auditd) to record privileged command use and user identities.\nAudit rules on /usr/bin/podman, /usr/bin/sudo, and related tools capture both the executed command and the initiating user, ensuring accountability and full‑text logging of privileged actions.\nPodman itself does not duplicate audit functionality, relying on host audit services for this control."},{"group_id_src":"V-233052","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233052","title":"SRG-APP-000111","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233052","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform components must provide the ability to send audit logs to a central enterprise repository for review and analysis.","rule_id_src":"SV-233052r960918_rule","rule_id":"SV-233052r960918","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000111-CTR-000220","rule_title":"The container platform components must provide the ability to send audit logs to a central enterprise repository for review and analysis.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform components to send audit logs to a central managed audit log repository.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the configuration settings to determine if the container platform components are configured to send audit events to central managed audit log repository. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to send audit events to central managed audit log repository, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform components must send audit events to a central managed audit log repository to provide reporting, analysis, and alert notification. Incident response relies on successful timely, accurate system analysis in order for the organization to identify and respond to possible security events.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000154"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"fce1059e-b92b-4dd8-b1d2-32b837af84a9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not directly perform auditing or manage audit logs.\nAll audit records, including container start, stop, and execution events, are collected and timestamped by the host’s RHEL 9 auditd and journald services.\nThese system components capture the container identifier and user context for each Podman action, ensuring all relevant container activity is included in host audit records.\nTherefore, auditing controls are fulfilled through the operating system’s audit mechanisms rather than Podman itself.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233055","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233055","title":"SRG-APP-000116","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233055","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use internal system clocks to generate audit record time stamps.","rule_id_src":"SV-233055r960927_rule","rule_id":"SV-233055r960927","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000116-CTR-000235","rule_title":"The container platform must use internal system clocks to generate audit record time stamps.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use internal system clocks to generate time stamps for log records.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration files to determine if the internal system clock is used for time stamps. \n\nIf the container platform does not use the internal system clock to generate time stamps, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Understanding when and sequence of events for an incident is crucial to understand what may have taken place. Without a common clock, the components generating audit events could be out of synchronization and would then present a picture of the event that is warped and corrupted. To give a clear picture, it is important that the container platform and its components use a common internal clock.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000159"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ba86374e-3b2c-4e86-9a41-a89411371413","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman uses the host system’s time source for all logging and event timestamps.\nThe RHEL 9 host synchronizes its internal system clock through chronyd/NTP, ensuring consistent audit and container log times across services.\nBecause Podman inherits timestamps directly from the host OS, it meets the requirement to use internal system clocks for audit record generation."},{"group_id_src":"V-233056","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233056","title":"SRG-APP-000118","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233056","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from any type of unauthorized read access.","rule_id_src":"SV-233056r960930_rule","rule_id":"SV-233056r960930","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000118-CTR-000240","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from any type of unauthorized read access.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect the storage of audit information from unauthorized read access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine where audit information is stored. \n\nIf the audit information is not protected from any type of unauthorized read access, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If audit data were to become compromised, then competent forensic analysis and discovery of the true source of potentially malicious system activity is difficult if not impossible to achieve. In addition, access to audit records provides information an attacker could potentially use to his or her advantage.\n\nTo ensure the veracity of audit data, the information system and/or the application must protect audit information from any and all unauthorized access. This includes read, write, and copy access.\n\nThis requirement can be achieved through multiple methods, which will depend upon system architecture and design. Commonly employed methods for protecting audit information include least privilege permissions as well as restricting the location and number of log file repositories.\n\nAdditionally, applications with user interfaces to audit records should not allow for the unfettered manipulation of or access to those records via the application. If the application provides access to the audit data, the application becomes accountable for ensuring audit information is protected from unauthorized access.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000162"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"9335f7b9-1552-4e09-bef2-7d8ad1f80829","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233057","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233057","title":"SRG-APP-000119","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233057","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from unauthorized modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-233057r960933_rule","rule_id":"SV-233057r960933","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000119-CTR-000245","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from unauthorized modification.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect the storage of audit information from unauthorized modification.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine where audit information is stored. \n\nIf the audit log data is not protected from unauthorized modification, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If audit data were to become compromised, then forensic analysis and discovery of the true source of potentially malicious system activity would be impossible to achieve.\n\nTo ensure the veracity of audit data, the information system and/or the application must protect audit information from unauthorized modification.\n\nThis requirement can be achieved through multiple methods, which will depend upon system architecture and design. Some commonly employed methods include ensuring log files receive the proper file system permissions and limiting log data locations.\n\nApplications providing a user interface to audit data will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the data and the corresponding rights that the user enjoys in order to make access decisions regarding the modification of audit data.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000163"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"52aeda2d-8a78-4fd3-ab46-8701c6d41d23","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233058","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233058","title":"SRG-APP-000120","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233058","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from unauthorized deletion.","rule_id_src":"SV-233058r960936_rule","rule_id":"SV-233058r960936","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000120-CTR-000250","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit information from unauthorized deletion.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect the storage of audit information from unauthorized deletion.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine where audit information is stored. \n\nIf the audit log data is not protected from unauthorized deletion, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If audit data were to become compromised, then forensic analysis and discovery of the true source of potentially malicious system activity would be impossible to achieve.\n\nTo ensure the veracity of audit data, the information system and/or the application must protect audit information from unauthorized deletion. This requirement can be achieved through multiple methods, which will depend upon system architecture and design.\n\nSome commonly employed methods include: ensuring log files receive the proper file system permissions utilizing file system protections, restricting access, and backing up log data to ensure log data is retained.\n\nApplications providing a user interface to audit data will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the data and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order make access decisions regarding the deletion of audit data.\n\nAudit information includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity. Audit information may include data from other applications or be included with the audit application itself.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000164"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2f2f18ef-84e3-4136-8d7f-3450db2760d9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233059","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233059","title":"SRG-APP-000121","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233059","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","rule_id_src":"SV-233059r960939_rule","rule_id":"SV-233059r960939","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000121-CTR-000255","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect audit tools from unauthorized access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to validate container platform audit tools are protected from unauthorized access. \n\nIf the audit tools are not protected from unauthorized access, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nApplications providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order to make access decisions regarding the access to audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001493"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2b57cf71-ceaa-4a1f-a222-f1bf15e5e481","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233060","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233060","title":"SRG-APP-000122","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233060","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","rule_id_src":"SV-233060r960942_rule","rule_id":"SV-233060r960942","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000122-CTR-000260","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect audit tools from unauthorized modification.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to validate container platform audit tools are protected from unauthorized modification. \n\nIf the audit tools are not protected from unauthorized modification, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nApplications providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order make access decisions regarding the modification of audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001494"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c1cf42ba-cbe6-4ac8-b29f-a75f6c75c4e8","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233061","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233061","title":"SRG-APP-000123","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233061","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","rule_id_src":"SV-233061r960945_rule","rule_id":"SV-233061r960945","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000123-CTR-000265","rule_title":"The container platform must protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect audit tools from unauthorized deletion.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to validate container platform audit tools are protected from unauthorized deletion. \n\nIf the audit tools are not protected from unauthorized deletion, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Protecting audit data also includes identifying and protecting the tools used to view and manipulate log data. Therefore, protecting audit tools is necessary to prevent unauthorized operation on audit data.\n\nApplications providing tools to interface with audit data will leverage user permissions and roles identifying the user accessing the tools and the corresponding rights the user enjoys in order make access decisions regarding the deletion of audit tools.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor-provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001495"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4ef30c92-5ff6-4f5d-840f-8d9787ded17c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a container runtime and does not include or manage audit tools—these functions are provided by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system (auditd and journald).\nBecause Podman does not supply or control any audit or log utilities of its own, responsibility for protecting those tools lies with the host OS.\nTherefore, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233063","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233063","title":"SRG-APP-000126","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233063","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use FIPS validated cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of log information.","rule_id_src":"SV-233063r960951_rule","rule_id":"SV-233063r960951","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000126-CTR-000275","rule_title":"The container platform must use FIPS validated cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of log information.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use FIPS-validated cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of log information.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if FIPS-validated cryptographic mechanisms are being used to protect the integrity of log information. \n\nIf FIPS-validated cryptographic mechanisms are not being used to protect the integrity of log information, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To fully investigate an incident and to have trust in the audit data that is generated, it is important to put in place data protections. Without integrity protections, unauthorized changes may be made to the audit files and reliable forensic analysis and discovery of the source of malicious system activity may be degraded. Although digital signatures are one example of protecting integrity, this control is not intended to cause a new cryptographic hash to be generated every time a record is added to a log file. \n\nIntegrity protections can also be implemented by using cryptographic techniques for security function isolation and file system protections to protect against unauthorized changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001350"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"fd3427a8-9f0c-454d-8b49-5dedf6d3921b","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe RHEL 9 host is operating in FIPS mode, ensuring all cryptographic operations—including those protecting system and container logs—use FIPS‑validated algorithms.\nPodman relies on system logging services (journald, auditd) which automatically use these validated mechanisms and maintain file integrity through permission and SELinux controls.\nThis protects log data against unauthorized modification and satisfies the requirement for FIPS‑approved integrity protections."},{"group_id_src":"V-233064","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233064","title":"SRG-APP-000131","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233064","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must be built from verified packages.","rule_id_src":"SV-233064r981843_rule","rule_id":"SV-233064r981843","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000131-CTR-000280","rule_title":"The container platform must be built from verified packages.","fix_text":"Rebuild the container platform from verified packages that are digitally signed by known and approved sources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to verify it has been built from packages that are digitally signed by known and approved sources. \n\nIf the container platform was built from packages that are not digitally signed or are from unknown or nonapproved sources, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"It is important to patch and upgrade the container platform when patches and upgrades are available. More important is to get these patches and upgrades from a known source. To validate the authenticity of any patches and upgrades before installation, the container platform must check that the files are digitally signed by sources approved by the organization.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003992"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ca526247-be63-42f2-9d28-92ccc4b22e75","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman is installed and maintained through the official RHEL 9 repositories, where all packages are digitally signed by Red Hat and verified automatically by DNF and GPG keys (/etc/pki/rpm-gpg/RPM-GPG-KEY-redhat-release).\nSystem updates are applied only from these trusted vendor sources, ensuring all container runtime components originate from verified, approved packages."},{"group_id_src":"V-233065","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233065","title":"SRG-APP-000131","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233065","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must verify container images.","rule_id_src":"SV-233065r981844_rule","rule_id":"SV-233065r981844","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000131-CTR-000285","rule_title":"The container platform must verify container images.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to verify container images are digitally signed and the signature is from a recognized and approved source.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if container images are verified by enforcing image signing and that the image is signed recognized by an approved source. \n\nIf container images are not verified or the signature is not verified as a recognized and approved source, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform must be capable of validating container images are signed and that the digital signature is from a recognized and approved source approved by the organization. Allowing any container image to be introduced into the registry and instantiated into a container can allow for services to be introduced that are not trusted and may contain malicious code, which introduces unwanted services. These unwanted services can cause harm and security risks to the hosting server, the container platform, other services running within the container platform, and the overall organization.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003992"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"32dc4fcf-c9a7-40e7-940d-781b3b823656","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nSystem‑wide image signature enforcement is not enabled because operational requirements occasionally require use of locally‑built or unsigned vendor images.\nPodman verifies trusted images through explicit configuration of /etc/containers/policy.json for approved Red Hat registries, while all other images are restricted by administrator control and change‑management review."},{"group_id_src":"V-233066","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233066","title":"SRG-APP-000133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233066","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform registry.","rule_id_src":"SV-233066r960960_rule","rule_id":"SV-233066r960960","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000133-CTR-000290","rule_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform registry.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use and enforce user privileges when accessing the container platform registry.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform registry configuration to determine if the level of access to the registry is controlled through user privileges. \r\n\r\nAttempt to perform registry operations to determine if the privileges are enforced. \r\n\r\nIf the container platform registry is not limited through user privileges or the user privileges are not enforced, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To control what is instantiated within the container platform, it is important to control access to the registry. Without this control, container images can be introduced and instantiated by accident or on container platform startup. Without control of the registry, security measures put in place for the runtime can be bypassed meaning the controls of approval and testing are also bypassed. Only those individuals and roles approved by the organization can have access to the container platform registry.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"9bb4cdb5-9e89-4176-9cd5-d5298f1bcd5e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not include or manage a container registry.\nAny registry (such as the internal GitLab instance) is an external service and out of scope for the Podman runtime.\nBecause Podman only interacts with pre‑defined registry endpoints and cannot control registry access or privileges, this requirement is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233067","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233067","title":"SRG-APP-000133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233067","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform runtime.","rule_id_src":"SV-233067r960960_rule","rule_id":"SV-233067r960960","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000133-CTR-000295","rule_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform runtime.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use and enforce user privileges when accessing the container platform runtime.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform runtime configuration to determine if the level of access to the runtime is controlled through user privileges. \n\nAttempt to perform runtime operations to determine if the privileges are enforced. \n\nIf the container platform runtime is not limited through user privileges or the user privileges are not enforced, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To control what is instantiated within the container platform, it is important to control access to the runtime. Without this control, container platform specific services and customer services can be introduced without receiving approval and going through proper testing. Only those individuals and roles approved by the organization can have access to the container platform runtime.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3946d83e-6f64-4765-a732-7aed04eebfba","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nAccess to the Podman container runtime on RHEL 9 is restricted to authorized administrators only.\nThe Podman binary (/usr/bin/podman) is owned by root and group‑restricted (chmod 750 /usr/bin/podman) so only approved users in the container‑admins group can execute runtime commands.\nNon‑privileged users cannot access or modify runtime functions, ensuring that only organization‑approved personnel can manage containers"},{"group_id_src":"V-233068","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233068","title":"SRG-APP-000133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233068","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform keystore.","rule_id_src":"SV-233068r960960_rule","rule_id":"SV-233068r960960","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000133-CTR-000300","rule_title":"The container platform must limit privileges to the container platform keystore.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use and enforce user privileges when accessing the container platform keystore.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform keystore configuration to determine if the level of access to the keystore is controlled through user privileges. \r\n\r\nAttempt to perform keystore operations to determine if the privileges are enforced. \r\n\r\nIf the container platform keystore is not limited through user privileges or the user privileges are not enforced, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform keystore is used to store credentials used to build a trust between the container platform and some external source. This trust relationship is authorized by the organization. If a malicious user were to have access to the container platform keystore, two negative scenarios could develop:\n\n1) Keys not approved could be introduced and \n2) Approved keys deleted, leading to the introduction of container images from sources that were never approved by the organization. \n\nTo thwart this threat, it is important to protect the container platform keystore and give access to only those individuals and roles approved by the organization.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"dbfd87f8-a511-4109-9419-759756f22153","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nodman does not host or manage a registry keystore.\nIt relies on the system’s certificate store for secure TLS communication and does not control registry keys or trust relationships directly.\nSince no internal keystore or privilege assignments exist within the runtime, this requirement is not applicable to Podman."},{"group_id_src":"V-233069","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233069","title":"SRG-APP-000133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233069","severity":"medium","group_title":"Configuration files for the container platform must be protected.","rule_id_src":"SV-233069r960960_rule","rule_id":"SV-233069r960960","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000133-CTR-000305","rule_title":"Configuration files for the container platform must be protected.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to only allow configuration modifications by privileged users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to verify that configuration files cannot be modified by non-privileged users. \n\nIf non-privileged users can modify configuration files, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The secure configuration of the container platform must be protected by disallowing changes to be implemented by non-privileged users. Changes to the container platform can introduce security risks or stability issues and undermine change management procedures. Securing configuration files from non-privileged user modification can be enforced using file ownership and permissions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"e3cea3f1-20c6-4266-a1cb-dda801be0d19","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 hosts running Podman restrict modification of container platform configuration files (/etc/containers/containers.conf, storage.conf, policy.json, etc.) to privileged users.\nThese files are owned by root and have read‑only permissions for others (root:root 0644), preventing changes by non‑privileged users.\nThis ensures Podman configuration integrity and complies with the requirement to protect runtime configuration files."},{"group_id_src":"V-233070","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233070","title":"SRG-APP-000133","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233070","severity":"medium","group_title":"Authentication files for the container platform must be protected.","rule_id_src":"SV-233070r960960_rule","rule_id":"SV-233070r960960","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000133-CTR-000310","rule_title":"Authentication files for the container platform must be protected.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to only allow authentication file modifications by privileged users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to verify that authentication files cannot be modified by non-privileged users. \n\nIf non-privileged users can modify key and certificate files, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The secure configuration of the container platform must be protected by disallowing changing to be implemented by non-privileged users. Changes to the container platform can introduce security risks and stability issues and undermine change management procedures. To secure authentication files from non-privileged user modification can be enforced using file ownership and permissions.\n\nExamples of authentication files are keys, certificates, and tokens.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001499"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"961b09c2-e41e-4059-90d8-c5ad70791bf1","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 hosts running Podman store authentication files such as TLS certificates, registry tokens, and keys under /etc/containers/ and root‑owned directories.\nFile ownership and permissions restrict modification to administrative users only (root:root 0644); non‑privileged users have read‑only or no access.\nThis protects all Podman authentication materials from unauthorized changes."},{"group_id_src":"V-233071","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233071","title":"SRG-APP-000141","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233071","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must be configured with only essential configurations.","rule_id_src":"SV-233071r960963_rule","rule_id":"SV-233071r960963","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000141-CTR-000315","rule_title":"The container platform must be configured with only essential configurations.","fix_text":"Identify the role the container platform is intended to play in the production environment and remove any components that are not needed or used for the intended purpose.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration and verify that only those components needed for operation are installed. \n\nIf components are installed that are not used for the intended purpose of the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform can be built with components that are not used for the intended purpose of the organization. To limit the attack surface of the container platform, it is essential that the non-essential services are not installed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b080d3a9-e62b-4bf8-ac9f-fb8fd04769ec","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nconfigured only with the essential Podman container runtime packages required for operation.\nNo unnecessary tools such as Buildah, Skopeo, or other optional components are installed, minimizing the attack surface and limiting system services to those directly supporting container execution."},{"group_id_src":"V-233072","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233072","title":"SRG-APP-000141","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233072","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform registry must contain only container images for those capabilities being offered by the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233072r960963_rule","rule_id":"SV-233072r960963","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000141-CTR-000320","rule_title":"The container platform registry must contain only container images for those capabilities being offered by the container platform.","fix_text":"Remove all container images from the container platform registry that are not being used or contain features and functions not supported by the platform.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform registry and the container images being stored. \n\nIf container images are stored in the registry and are not being used to offer container platform capabilities, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Allowing container images to reside within the container platform registry that are not essential to the capabilities being offered by the container platform becomes a potential security risk. By allowing these non-essential container images to exist, the possibility for accidental instantiation exists. The images may be unpatched, not supported, or offer non-approved capabilities. Those images for customer services are considered essential capabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000381"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ba351386-69cd-4b88-896a-2bc2855cd925","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nonly applicable images are stored on the system."},{"group_id_src":"V-233073","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233073","title":"SRG-APP-000142","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233073","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must enforce ports, protocols, and services that adhere to the PPSM CAL.","rule_id_src":"SV-233073r1043177_rule","rule_id":"SV-233073r1043177","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000142-CTR-000325","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must enforce ports, protocols, and services that adhere to the PPSM CAL.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to disable any ports or protocols that are prohibited by the PPSM CAL and not necessary for the operation.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform documentation and deployment configuration to determine which ports and protocols are enabled. \r\n\r\nVerify the ports and protocols being used are not prohibited by PPSM CAL in accordance to DoD Instruction 8551.01 Policy and are necessary for the operations and applications.\r\n\r\nIf any of the ports or protocols is prohibited or not necessary for the operation, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Ports, protocols, and services within the container platform runtime must be controlled and conform to the PPSM CAL. Those ports, protocols, and services that fall outside the PPSM CAL must be blocked by the runtime. Instructions on the PPSM can be found in DoD Instruction 8551.01 Policy.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b0d0748d-16bf-462a-92f4-7e8b098623a5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman itself does not run any kind of daemon or listener on any port. it is command line only."},{"group_id_src":"V-233074","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233074","title":"SRG-APP-000142","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233074","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must enforce the use of ports that are non-privileged.","rule_id_src":"SV-233074r1043177_rule","rule_id":"SV-233074r1043177","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000142-CTR-000330","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must enforce the use of ports that are non-privileged.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to disallow the use of privileged ports by containers. Move any containers that are using privileged ports to non-privileged ports.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration and the containers within the platform by performing the following checks:\n\n1. Verify the container platform is configured to disallow the use of privileged ports by containers.\n2. Validate all containers within the container platform are using non-privileged ports.\n3. Attempt to instantiate a container image that uses a privileged port.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to disallow the use of privileged ports, this is a finding.\n\nIf the container platform has containers using privileged ports, this is a finding.\n\nIf the container platform allows containers to be instantiated that use privileged ports, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Privileged ports are those ports below 1024 and that require system privileges for their use. If containers are able to use these ports, the container must be run as a privileged user. The container platform must stop containers that try to map to these ports directly. Allowing non-privileged ports to be mapped to the container-privileged port is the allowable method when a certain port is needed. An example is mapping port 8080 externally to port 80 in the container.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000382"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b3e34078-c0ee-4981-afb3-d8b75a4b661a","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman run in \"rootless\" mode, meaning it cannot bind to ports below 1024."},{"group_id_src":"V-233075","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233075","title":"SRG-APP-000148","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233075","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify and authenticate users.","rule_id_src":"SV-233075r1051115_rule","rule_id":"SV-233075r1051115","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000148-CTR-000335","rule_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify and authenticate users.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to uniquely identify and authenticate users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if users are uniquely identified and authenticated. \n\nIf users are not uniquely identified or are not authenticated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform requires user accounts to perform container platform tasks. These tasks may pertain to the overall container platform or may be component-specific, thus requiring users to authenticate against those specific components. To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, users must be identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"dc1312d4-9b42-4f1b-b4ea-2b8bd52c3164","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe podman platform does not perform authentication tasks. This is handled by the host that has podman installed. In order for a user to be able to run any podman command, they have to first authenticate to the operating system, which has local accounts as well as active directory integration. Therefore since podman does not handle any authentication for identity, this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233076","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233076","title":"SRG-APP-000148","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233076","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform application program interface (API) must uniquely identify and authenticate users.","rule_id_src":"SV-233076r1051115_rule","rule_id":"SV-233076r1051115","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000148-CTR-000340","rule_title":"The container platform application program interface (API) must uniquely identify and authenticate users.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to uniquely identify and authenticate users before container platform API access.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if users are uniquely identified and authenticated before the API is executed. \n\nIf users are not uniquely identified or are not authenticated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform requires user accounts to perform container platform tasks. These tasks are often performed through the container platform API. Protecting the API from users who are not authorized or authenticated is essential to keep the container platform stable. Protection of platform and application data and enhances the protections put in place for Denial-of Service (DoS) attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ca11ae41-c183-4334-a2e6-c54740889f71","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman has no interactive api, it is cmdline execution only."},{"group_id_src":"V-233077","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233077","title":"SRG-APP-000148","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233077","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of the users.","rule_id_src":"SV-233077r1051115_rule","rule_id":"SV-233077r1051115","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000148-CTR-000345","rule_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of the users.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if processes acting on behalf of users are uniquely identified and authenticated. \n\nIf processes acting on behalf of users are not uniquely identified or are not authenticated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform will instantiate a container image and use the user privileges given to the user used to execute the container. To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access to containers, the user the container is using to execute must be uniquely identified and authenticated to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3e0b1b97-b0c9-430d-a52c-c974f3dd1529","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman processes only run as the user, they do not run as other users or on behalf of other users."},{"group_id_src":"V-233078","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233078","title":"SRG-APP-000148","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233078","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform application program interface (API) must uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of the users.","rule_id_src":"SV-233078r1051115_rule","rule_id":"SV-233078r1051115","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000148-CTR-000350","rule_title":"The container platform application program interface (API) must uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of the users.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform API to uniquely identify and authenticate processes acting on behalf of users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform API configuration to determine if processes acting on behalf of users are uniquely identified and authenticated. \n\nIf processes acting on behalf of users are not uniquely identified or are not authenticated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform API can be used to perform any task within the platform. Often, the API is used to create tasks that perform some kind of maintenance task and run without user interaction. To guarantee the task is authorized, it is important to authenticate the task. These tasks, even though executed without user intervention, run on behalf of a user and must run with the user's authorization. If tasks are allowed to be created without authentication, users could bypass authentication and authorization mechanisms put in place for user interfaces. This could lead to users gaining greater access than given to the user putting the container platform into a compromised state.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000764"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5f791239-ceab-4e10-b36f-200258ff39ca","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman has no interactive api, it is cmdline execution only."},{"group_id_src":"V-233079","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233079","title":"SRG-APP-000149","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233079","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for network access to privileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233079r960972_rule","rule_id":"SV-233079r960972","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000149-CTR-000355","rule_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for network access to privileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use multifactor authentication for network access to privileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to use multifactor authentication for network access to privileged accounts. \n\nIf the container platform does not use multifactor authentication for network access to privileged accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without the use of multifactor authentication, the ease of access to privileged functions is greatly increased.\n\nMultifactor authentication requires using two or more factors to achieve authentication.\n\nFactors include: \n(i) something a user knows (e.g., password/PIN); \n(ii) something a user has (e.g., cryptographic identification device, token); or \n(iii) something a user is (e.g., biometric).\n\nA privileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a privileged user.\n\nNetwork access is defined as access to an information system by a user (or a process acting on behalf of a user) communicating through a network (e.g., local area network, wide area network, or the internet).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000765"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4f6e5d3b-7258-49e7-b6f2-c85027f93ab2","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not provide any remote login or account authentication services over the network.\nAll privileged user authentication is handled by the RHEL 9 domain‑joined host, using standard domain credentials verified through LDAP/AD.\nBecause Podman inherits the authenticated host session and cannot enforce multifactor authentication itself, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233080","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233080","title":"SRG-APP-000150","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233080","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for network access to non-privileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233080r960975_rule","rule_id":"SV-233080r960975","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000150-CTR-000360","rule_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for network access to non-privileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use multifactor authentication for network access to non-privileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to use multifactor authentication for network access to non-privileged accounts. \n\nIf the container platform does not use multifactor authentication for network access to non-privileged accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, non-privileged users must utilize multifactor authentication to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nMultifactor authentication uses two or more factors to achieve authentication.\n\nFactors include: \n(i) Something you know (e.g., password/PIN); \n(ii) Something you have (e.g., cryptographic identification device, token); or \n(iii) Something you are (e.g., biometric).\n\nA non-privileged account is any information system account with authorizations of a non-privileged user.\n\nNetwork access is any access to an application by a user (or process acting on behalf of a user) where said access is obtained through a network connection.\n\nApplications integrating with the DoD Active Directory and utilize the DoD CAC are examples of compliant multifactor authentication solutions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000766"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"6144302b-c2a9-4f1e-b584-0407a147c0cb","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not provide or control user logins over the network; it relies on the RHEL 9 domain‑joined host for authentication.\nUser network access is handled through the organization’s directory services (e.g., Active Directory/LDAP) using standard username + password credentials.\nBecause Podman has no internal mechanism to enforce multifactor authentication and MFA is not implemented on the domain, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233081","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233081","title":"SRG-APP-000151","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233081","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for local access to privileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233081r981845_rule","rule_id":"SV-233081r981845","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000151-CTR-000365","rule_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for local access to privileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use multifactor authentication for local access to privileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if multifactor authentication is used for local access to privileged accounts. \n\nIf multifactor authentication for local access to privileged accounts is not being used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To ensure accountability and prevent unauthenticated access, privileged users must utilize multifactor authentication to prevent potential misuse and compromise of the system.\n\nMultifactor authentication is defined as using two or more factors to achieve authentication.\n\nFactors include: \n(i) Something a user knows (e.g., password/PIN); \n(ii) Something a user has (e.g., cryptographic identification device, token); or \n(iii) Something a user is (e.g., biometric).\n\nA privileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a privileged user.\n\nLocal access is defined as access to an organizational information system by a user (or process acting on behalf of a user) communicating through a direct connection without the use of a network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000765"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b62c8b38-dd40-4fd9-a77a-e49b63cca4ec","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman relies entirely on the RHEL 9 host’s domain authentication for user and privilege access.\nUser sign‑in and administrative access are managed through the organization’s domain controller using standard username and password credentials; Podman itself provides no separate authentication.\nBecause the container runtime inherits the authenticated host session and has no built‑in method to enforce MFA, this requirement is not applicable to Podman"},{"group_id_src":"V-233082","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233082","title":"SRG-APP-000152","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233082","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for local access to nonprivileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233082r981848_rule","rule_id":"SV-233082r981848","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000152-CTR-000370","rule_title":"The container platform must use multifactor authentication for local access to nonprivileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use multifactor authentication for local access to nonprivileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if multifactor authentication is used for local access to nonprivileged accounts. \n\nIf multifactor authentication for local access to nonprivileged accounts is not being used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To ensure accountability, prevent unauthenticated access, and prevent misuse of the system, nonprivileged users must utilize multi-factor authentication for local access.\n\nMultifactor authentication is defined as using two or more factors to achieve authentication.\n\nFactors include: \n(i) Something a user knows (e.g., password/PIN); \n(ii) Something a user has (e.g., cryptographic identification device, token); or \n(iii) Something a user is (e.g., biometric).\n\nA nonprivileged account is defined as an information system account with authorizations of a regular or nonprivileged user.\n\nLocal access is defined as access to an organizational information system by a user (or process acting on behalf of a user) communicating through a direct connection without the use of a network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000766"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"387dddb8-882f-4f01-8073-68e73a1e13db","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman is a local, daemonless container runtime that does not provide its own user login mechanism.\nAll user authentication and MFA enforcement occur at the RHEL 9 host OS level.\nSince Podman inherits the authenticated host session and has no additional local user authentication, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233083","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233083","title":"SRG-APP-000153","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233083","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must ensure users are authenticated with an individual authenticator prior to using a group authenticator.","rule_id_src":"SV-233083r981849_rule","rule_id":"SV-233083r981849","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000153-CTR-000375","rule_title":"The container platform must ensure users are authenticated with an individual authenticator prior to using a group authenticator.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to ensure users are authenticated with an individual authenticator prior to using a group authenticator.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to ensure users are authenticated with an individual authenticator prior to using a group authenticator. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to ensure users are authenticated with an individual authenticator prior to using a group authenticator, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To ensure individual accountability and prevent unauthorized access, application users must be individually identified and authenticated.\n\nIndividual accountability mandates that each user be uniquely identified. A group authenticator is a shared account or some other form of authentication that allows multiple unique individuals to access the application using a single account.\n\nIf an application allows or provides for group authenticators, it must first individually authenticate users prior to implementing group authenticator functionality.\n\nSome applications may not need to provide a group authenticator; this is considered a matter of application design. In those instances where the application design includes the use of a group authenticator, this requirement will apply.\n\nThere may also be instances when specific user actions need to be performed on the information system without unique user identification or authentication. An example of this type of access is a web server, which contains publicly releasable information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004045"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2a2d5acd-2bb7-484e-bd46-4b502428506f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman on RHEL 9 does not manage or authenticate users directly and has no group or shared authenticator feature.\nUser authentication occurs through the host operating system or external identity services (e.g., LDAP/AD), where each user signs in with individual credentials.\nBecause Podman inherits the authenticated user’s session and does not support shared accounts, this requirement is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233084","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233084","title":"SRG-APP-000156","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233084","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use FIPS-validated SHA-1 or higher hash function to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to privileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233084r960993_rule","rule_id":"SV-233084r960993","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000156-CTR-000380","rule_title":"The container platform must use FIPS-validated SHA-1 or higher hash function to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to privileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use FIPS-validated SHA-1 or higher hash function to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to privileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to use FIPS-validated SHA-1 or higher hash function to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to privileged accounts. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to use FIPS-validated SHA-1 or higher hash function to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to privileged accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"A replay attack may enable an unauthorized user to gain access to the application. Authentication sessions between the authenticator and the application validating the user credentials must not be vulnerable to a replay attack.\n\nAnti-replay is a cryptographically based mechanism; thus, it must use FIPS-approved algorithms. An authentication process resists replay attacks if it is impractical to achieve a successful authentication by recording and replaying a previous authentication message. Note that the anti-replay service is implicit when data contains monotonically increasing sequence numbers and data integrity is assured. Use of DoD PKI is inherently compliant with this requirement for user and device access. Use of Transport Layer Security (TLS), including application protocols such as HTTPS and DNSSEC, that use TLS/SSL as the underlying security protocol is also compliant.\n\nConfigure the information system to use the hash message authentication code (HMAC) algorithm for authentication services to Kerberos, SSH, web management tool, and any other access method.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001941"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a8634f5c-2535-4fb2-8c2a-d60e0726e229","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not provide its own network authentication or privilege services.\nOn RHEL 9, replay‑resistant authentication is enforced by the host operating system’s FIPS‑mode configuration, which uses FIPS‑validated cryptographic modules and TLS 1.2 / 1.3 for SSH, HTTPS, and registry access.\nAll Podman network operations (e.g., image pulls, registry login) inherit these FIPS‑compliant algorithms"},{"group_id_src":"V-233085","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233085","title":"SRG-APP-000157","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233085","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must implement replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to nonprivileged accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233085r981852_rule","rule_id":"SV-233085r981852","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000157-CTR-000385","rule_title":"The container platform must implement replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to nonprivileged accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to nonprivileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to nonprivileged accounts. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to provide replay-resistant authentication mechanisms for network access to nonprivileged accounts, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"A replay attack may enable an unauthorized user to gain access to the application. Authentication sessions between the authenticator and the application validating the user credentials must not be vulnerable to a replay attack.\n\nAn authentication process resists replay attacks if it is impractical to achieve a successful authentication by recording and replaying a previous authentication message.\n\nA nonprivileged account is any operating system account with authorizations of a nonprivileged user.\n\nTechniques used to address this include protocols using nonces (e.g., numbers generated for a specific one-time use) or challenges (e.g., TLS, WS_Security). Additional techniques include time-synchronous or challenge-response one-time authenticators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001941"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5683ffcb-d137-44ac-a16f-8283783e08ca","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025Podman is a daemonless local container runtime and does not provide or manage network login or authentication services for user access.\nUser authentication, including replay‑resistant network mechanisms such as SSH or Kerberos, is handled entirely by the RHEL 9 host operating system or enterprise identity infrastructure (e.g., AD/LDAP with GSSAPI).\nBecause Podman itself has no built‑in authentication system or remote network service, there are no network login or credential replay vectors within the container runtime to which this control could apply.\nConsequently, the requirement is fulfilled by the host OS’s secure, replay‑resistant protocols, and the STIG item is Not Applicable to Podman."},{"group_id_src":"V-233086","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233086","title":"SRG-APP-000158","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233086","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify all network-connected nodes before establishing any connection.","rule_id_src":"SV-233086r960999_rule","rule_id":"SV-233086r960999","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000158-CTR-000390","rule_title":"The container platform must uniquely identify all network-connected nodes before establishing any connection.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to uniquely identify all nodes before establishing the connection.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform uniquely identifies all nodes before establishing a connection. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to uniquely identify all nodes before establishing the connection, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"A container platform usually consists of multiple nodes. It is important for these nodes to be uniquely identified before a connection is allowed. Without identifying the nodes, unidentified or unknown nodes may be introduced, thereby facilitating malicious activity.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000778"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7ad8f0fc-6ecc-4e8b-a2ca-dda8d83692c1","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is not a network clustered style of container engine. this is not applicable"},{"group_id_src":"V-233087","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233087","title":"SRG-APP-000163","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233087","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must disable identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.","rule_id_src":"SV-233087r981853_rule","rule_id":"SV-233087r981853","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000163-CTR-000395","rule_title":"The container platform must disable identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to disable identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to disable identifiers (individuals, groups, roles, and devices) after 35 days of inactivity. \n\nIf identifiers are not disabled after 35 days of inactivity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Inactive identifiers pose a risk to systems and applications. Attackers that are able to exploit an inactive identifier can potentially obtain and maintain undetected access to the application. Owners of inactive accounts will not notice if unauthorized access to their user account has been obtained.\n\nApplications need to track periods of inactivity and disable application identifiers after 35 days of inactivity.\n\nManagement of user identifiers is not applicable to shared information system accounts (e.g., guest and anonymous accounts). It is commonly the case that a user account is the name of an information system account associated with an individual.\n\nTo avoid having to build complex user management capabilities directly into their application, wise developers leverage the underlying OS or other user account management infrastructure (AD, LDAP) that is already in place within the organization and meets organizational user account management requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003627"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"e1a335a4-ec95-47d3-a25f-1f5df6c3ce55","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman is a daemonless container runtime and does not implement, manage, or maintain local user identifiers or authentication databases.\nAccess to the container environment is entirely controlled by the underlying RHEL 9 operating system or external identity systems (AD, LDAP, or SSSD) configured on the host.\nAccount inactivity and expiration policies, including automatic disablement after 35 days, are enforced through the host’s PAM and chage or directory‑service configurations—not within Podman itself.\nSince user account management resides at the operating system or enterprise identity level, this control is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233088","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233088","title":"SRG-APP-000164","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233088","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce a minimum 15-character password length.","rule_id_src":"SV-233088r981854_rule","rule_id":"SV-233088r981854","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000164-CTR-000400","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce a minimum 15-character password length.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce a minimum 15-character password length.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform enforces a minimum 15-character password length. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce a 15-character password length, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nPassword complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks. Password length is one factor of several that helps to determine strength and how long it takes to crack a password. The shorter the password, the lower the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nUse of more characters in a password helps to exponentially increase the time and/or resources required to compromise the password.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"40262f20-9e8b-4d4b-a46e-da610a606865","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user credentials or provide any internal authentication mechanisms. All user authentication and password complexity enforcement are handled by the host operating system (RHEL 9) through PAM and /etc/security/pwquality.conf, which require at least one special character and other complexity rules. Since password policies are inherited from the OS and not configurable within Podman itself, this requirement is satisfied at the system level and is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233090","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233090","title":"SRG-APP-000166","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233090","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-233090r981856_rule","rule_id":"SV-233090r981856","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000166-CTR-000410","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one uppercase character be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determine how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password is, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"62abadd0-f01e-4890-8246-2f06a9478ef5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user credentials or provide any internal authentication mechanisms. All user authentication and password complexity enforcement are handled by the host operating system (RHEL 9) through PAM and /etc/security/pwquality.conf, which require at least one special character and other complexity rules. Since password policies are inherited from the OS and not configurable within Podman itself, this requirement is satisfied at the system level and is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233091","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233091","title":"SRG-APP-000167","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233091","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-233091r981857_rule","rule_id":"SV-233091r981857","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000167-CTR-000415","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one lowercase character be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determine how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5dbcc59a-1905-4ac6-8ff9-53e453024f0f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user credentials or provide any internal authentication mechanisms. All user authentication and password complexity enforcement are handled by the host operating system (RHEL 9) through PAM and /etc/security/pwquality.conf, which require at least one special character and other complexity rules. Since password policies are inherited from the OS and not configurable within Podman itself, this requirement is satisfied at the system level and is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233092","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233092","title":"SRG-APP-000168","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233092","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-233092r981858_rule","rule_id":"SV-233092r981858","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000168-CTR-000420","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one numeric character be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor of several that determine how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bf5a3320-d20a-4c34-ae16-752c75297e6f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user credentials or provide any internal authentication mechanisms. All user authentication and password complexity enforcement are handled by the host operating system (RHEL 9) through PAM and /etc/security/pwquality.conf, which require at least one special character and other complexity rules. Since password policies are inherited from the OS and not configurable within Podman itself, this requirement is satisfied at the system level and is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233093","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233093","title":"SRG-APP-000169","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233093","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","rule_id_src":"SV-233093r981859_rule","rule_id":"SV-233093r981859","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000169-CTR-000425","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce password complexity by requiring that at least one special character be used, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Use of a complex password helps to increase the time and resources required to compromise the password. Password complexity, or strength, is a measure of the effectiveness of a password in resisting attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nPassword complexity is one factor in determining how long it takes to crack a password. The more complex the password, the greater the number of possible combinations that need to be tested before the password is compromised.\n\nSpecial characters are those characters that are not alphanumeric. Examples include ~ ! @ # $ % ^ *.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"84e93e86-6182-4b6e-a59b-1f21f95e9d50","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not manage user credentials or provide any internal authentication mechanisms. All user authentication and password complexity enforcement are handled by the host operating system (RHEL 9) through PAM and /etc/security/pwquality.conf, which require at least one special character and other complexity rules. Since password policies are inherited from the OS and not configurable within Podman itself, this requirement is satisfied at the system level and is not applicable to the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233094","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233094","title":"SRG-APP-000170","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233094","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed.","rule_id_src":"SV-233094r1107119_rule","rule_id":"SV-233094r1107119","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000170-CTR-000430","rule_title":"The container platform must require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it requires the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed. \n\nIf the container platform does not require the change of at least eight of the total number of characters when passwords are changed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If the application allows the user to consecutively reuse extensive portions of passwords, this increases the chances of password compromise by increasing the window of opportunity for attempts at guessing and brute-force attacks.\n\nThe number of changed characters refers to the number of changes required with respect to the total number of positions in the current password. In other words, characters may be the same within the two passwords; however, the positions of the like characters must be different.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a11d8ed9-014d-47bb-b970-5bab3e93fc2e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"[root@mirhel9 ~]# cat /etc/security/pwquality.conf|grep dif\n# difok = 1\n# Per CCE-83564-5: Set difok = 8 in /etc/security/pwquality.conf\ndifok = 8\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe podman command runs as user level execution event. This requires them to login to the machine locally or over ssh. The machine itself is hardened to DOD standards for pw complexity and account limits."},{"group_id_src":"V-233095","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233095","title":"SRG-APP-000171","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233095","severity":"medium","group_title":"For container platform using password authentication, the application must store only cryptographic representations of passwords.","rule_id_src":"SV-233095r981861_rule","rule_id":"SV-233095r981861","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000171-CTR-000435","rule_title":"For container platform using password authentication, the application must store only cryptographic representations of passwords.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to store only cryptographic representations of passwords if passwords are being used for authentication.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it using password authentication and stores only cryptographic representations of the passwords. \n\nIf the container platform is using password authentication and does not store only cryptographic representations of passwords, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected at all times, and encryption is the standard method for protecting passwords. If passwords are not encrypted, they can be plainly read and easily compromised. Use of passwords for authentication is intended only for limited situations and should not be used as a replacement for two-factor common access card (CAC)-enabled authentication.\n\nExamples of situations where a user ID and password might be used include:\n\n- When the user does not use a CAC and is not a current DOD employee, member of the military, or DOD contractor.\n\n- When a user has been officially designated as temporarily unable to present a CAC for some reason (lost, damaged, not yet issued, broken card reader) (i.e., Temporary Exception User) and to satisfy urgent organizational needs must be temporarily permitted to use user ID/password authentication until the problem with CAC use has been remedied.\n\n- When the application is publicly available and or hosting publicly releasable data requiring some degree of need-to-know protection.\n\nIf the password is already encrypted and not a plaintext password, this meets this requirement. Implementation of this requirement requires configuration of FIPS-approved cipher block algorithm and block cipher modes for encryption. This method uses a one-way hashing encryption algorithm with a salt value to validate a user's password without having to store the actual password. Performance and time required to access are factors that must be considered, and the one-way hash is the most feasible means of securing the password and providing an acceptable measure of password security.\n\nVerifying the user knows a password is performed using a password verifier. In its simplest form, a password verifier is a computational function that is capable of creating a hash of a password and determining if the value provided by the user matches the hash. A more secure version of verifying a user knowing a password is to store the result of an iterating hash function and a large random salt value as follows:\n\nH0 = H(pwd, H(salt))\nHn = H(Hn-1,H(salt))\n\nIn the above, \"n\" is a cryptographically-strong random [*3] number. \"Hn\" is stored along with the salt. When the application wishes to verify that the user knows a password, it simply repeats the process and compares \"Hn\" with the stored \"Hn\". A salt is essentially a fixed-length cryptographically strong random value.\n\nAnother method is using a keyed-hash message authentication code (HMAC). HMAC calculates a message authentication code via a cryptographic hash function used in conjunction with an encryption key. The key must be protected as with any private key.\n\nThis requirement applies to all accounts including authentication server, AAA, and local account, including the root account and the account of last resort.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004062"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c4f64e7a-9999-4844-b45f-9ee3a4eebc80","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233096","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233096","title":"SRG-APP-000172","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233096","severity":"high","group_title":"For accounts using password authentication, the container platform must use FIPS-validated SHA-2 or later protocol to protect the integrity of the password authentication process.","rule_id_src":"SV-233096r961029_rule","rule_id":"SV-233096r961029","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000172-CTR-000440","rule_title":"For accounts using password authentication, the container platform must use FIPS-validated SHA-2 or later protocol to protect the integrity of the password authentication process.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to transmit only encrypted FIPS-validated SHA-2 or later representations of passwords.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform enforces the required FIPS-validated encrypt passwords when they are transmitted. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to meet this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Passwords need to be protected on entry, in transmission, during authentication, and when stored. If compromised at any of these security points, a nefarious user can use the password along with stolen user account information to gain access or to escalate privileges. The container platform may require account authentication during container platform tasks and before accessing container platform components, e.g. runtime, registry, and keystore.\n\nDuring any user authentication, the container platform must use FIPS-validated SHA-2 or later protocol to protect the integrity of the password authentication process.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000197"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3388446c-ae80-4373-9970-28686a8c42ce","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is a cli based application, not username/password information is exchanged. The host itself is fips compliant however"},{"group_id_src":"V-233097","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233097","title":"SRG-APP-000173","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233097","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce 24 hours (one day) as the minimum password lifetime.","rule_id_src":"SV-233097r981862_rule","rule_id":"SV-233097r981862","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000173-CTR-000445","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce 24 hours (one day) as the minimum password lifetime.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce 24 hours/1 day as the minimum password lifetime.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces 24 hours/1 day as the minimum password lifetime. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce 24 hours/1 day as the minimum password lifetime, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Enforcing a minimum password lifetime helps prevent repeated password changes to defeat the password reuse or history enforcement requirement.\n\nRestricting this setting limits the user's ability to change their password. Passwords need to be changed at specific policy-based intervals; however, if the application allows the user to immediately and continually change their password, then the password could be repeatedly changed in a short period of time to defeat the organization's policy regarding password reuse.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a62c5bee-0f22-4650-9611-1f8e59c10e30","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable.\n\nhowever, the host has this configured."},{"group_id_src":"V-233098","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233098","title":"SRG-APP-000174","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233098","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.","rule_id_src":"SV-233098r1043190_rule","rule_id":"SV-233098r1043190","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000174-CTR-000450","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it enforces a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce a 60-day maximum password lifetime restriction, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Any password, no matter how complex, can eventually be cracked; therefore, passwords need to be changed at specific intervals. \n\nOne method of minimizing this risk is to use complex passwords and periodically change them. If the application does not limit the lifetime of passwords and force users to change their passwords, there is the risk that the system and/or application passwords could be compromised. \n\nThis requirement does not include emergency administration accounts that are meant for access to the application in case of failure. These accounts are not required to have maximum password lifetime restrictions.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004066"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"a798c723-513a-4b09-9d15-b83df52943e8","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"from /etc/login.defs\n\nPASS_MAX_DAYS 60\nPASS_MIN_DAYS 1\nPASS_WARN_AGE   7\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe podman command runs as user level execution event. This requires them to login to the machine locally or over ssh. The machine itself is hardened to DOD standards for pw complexity and account limits."},{"group_id_src":"V-233101","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233101","title":"SRG-APP-000177","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233101","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must map the authenticated identity to the individual user or group account for PKI-based authentication.","rule_id_src":"SV-233101r961044_rule","rule_id":"SV-233101r961044","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000177-CTR-000465","rule_title":"The container platform must map the authenticated identity to the individual user or group account for PKI-based authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to utilize the DoD Enterprise PKI infrastructure.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to ensure the container platform provides a PKI integration capability that meets DoD PKI infrastructure requirements. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to meet this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform and its components may require authentication before use. When the authentication is PKI-based, the container platform or component must map the certificate to a user account. If the certificate is not mapped to a user account, the ability to determine the identity of the individual user or group will not be available for forensic analysis.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000187"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4c6e62d2-1512-4aac-b003-3d2b261f859f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233102","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233102","title":"SRG-APP-000178","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233102","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must obscure feedback of authentication information during the authentication process to protect the information from possible exploitation/use by unauthorized individuals.","rule_id_src":"SV-233102r961047_rule","rule_id":"SV-233102r961047","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000178-CTR-000470","rule_title":"The container platform must obscure feedback of authentication information during the authentication process to protect the information from possible exploitation/use by unauthorized individuals.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to obscure feedback of authentication information during the authentication process to protect the information from possible exploitation/use by unauthorized individuals.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation and configuration to determine if any interfaces that are provided for authentication purposes display the user's password when it is typed into the data entry field. \n\nIf authentication information is not obfuscated when entered, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To prevent the compromise of authentication information such as passwords during the authentication process, the feedback from the container platform and its components, e.g., runtime, registry, and keystore, must not provide any information that would allow an unauthorized user to compromise the authentication mechanism.\n\nObfuscation of user-provided information when typed is a method used in addressing this risk.\n\nDisplaying asterisks when a user types in a password is an example of obscuring feedback of authentication information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000206"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b9352bf9-b014-48ba-85a1-bc4257e75467","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233105","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233105","title":"SRG-APP-000181","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233105","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.","rule_id_src":"SV-233105r961056_rule","rule_id":"SV-233105r961056","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000181-CTR-000485","rule_title":"The container platform must provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to support on-demand reporting requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to provide an audit reduction capability that supports on-demand reporting requirements. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to support on-demand reporting requirements, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The ability to generate on-demand reports, including after the audit data has been subjected to audit reduction, greatly facilitates the organization's ability to generate incident reports as needed to better handle larger-scale or more complex security incidents. \n\nAudit reduction is a process that manipulates collected audit information and organizes such information in a summary format that is more meaningful to analysts. The report generation capability provided by the application must support on-demand (i.e., customizable, ad hoc, and as-needed) reports.\n\nThis requirement is specific to applications with audit reduction capabilities; however, applications need to support on-demand audit review and analysis.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001876"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"9658f40e-1c5f-4357-b830-8a62fd2509f3","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233106","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233106","title":"SRG-APP-000185","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233106","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must employ strong authenticators in the establishment of non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233106r961062_rule","rule_id":"SV-233106r961062","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000185-CTR-000490","rule_title":"The container platform must employ strong authenticators in the establishment of non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to employ strong authenticators in the establishment of non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the container platform is configured to employ strong authenticators in the establishment of non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to employ strong authenticators in the establishment of non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If maintenance tools are used by unauthorized personnel, they may accidentally or intentionally damage or compromise the system. The act of managing systems and applications includes the ability to access sensitive application information, such as, system configuration details, diagnostic information, user information, and potentially sensitive application data.\n\nNon-local maintenance and diagnostic activities are those activities conducted by individuals communicating through a network, either an external network (e.g., the internet) or an internal network. Local maintenance and diagnostic activities are those activities carried out by individuals physically present at the information system or information system component and not communicating across a network connection. Typically, strong authentication requires authenticators that are resistant to replay attacks and employ multifactor authentication. Strong authenticators include, for example, PKI where certificates are stored on a token protected by a password, passphrase, or biometric.\n\nThis requirement applies to hardware/software diagnostic test equipment or tools. This requirement does not cover hardware/software components that may support information system maintenance, yet are a part of the system (e.g., the software implementing \"ping,\" \"ls,\" \"ipconfig,\" or the hardware and software implementing the monitoring port of an Ethernet switch).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000877"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2696a4d3-6414-4fe7-b6df-09f5c833d3d9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233108","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233108","title":"SRG-APP-000190","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233108","severity":"medium","group_title":"The application must terminate all network connections associated with a communications session at the end of the session, or as follows: for in-band management sessions (privileged sessions), the session must be terminated after 10 minutes of inactivity.","rule_id_src":"SV-233108r961068_rule","rule_id":"SV-233108r961068","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000190-CTR-000500","rule_title":"The application must terminate all network connections associated with a communications session at the end of the session, or as follows: for in-band management sessions (privileged sessions), the session must be terminated after 10 minutes of inactivity.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to terminate user sessions on defined conditions or trigger events.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration settings to determine if the container platform is configured to close user sessions after defined conditions or trigger events are met.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured or cannot be configured to disconnect users after defined conditions and trigger events are met, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Terminating an idle session within a short time period reduces the window of opportunity for unauthorized personnel to take control of a management session enabled on the console or console port that has been left unattended. In addition, quickly terminating an idle session will also free up resources committed by the managed network element. \n\nTerminating network connections associated with communications sessions includes, for example, de-allocating associated TCP/IP address/port pairs at the operating system level, or de-allocating networking assignments at the application level if multiple application sessions are using a single, operating system level network connection. This does not mean that the application terminates all sessions or network access; it only ends the inactive session and releases the resources associated with that session.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001133"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"06f18460-3a23-41dc-9299-6fca29481b0d","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman on RHEL 9 is a daemonless container runtime, so each user or administrative session runs as a local process rather than a persistent network service.\nWhen a Podman CLI session ends, the associated process and any temporary network sockets terminate immediately, de‑allocating all resources.\nAdministrative remote access uses standard RHEL management protocols (e.g., SSH) that already enforce idle session timeouts through /etc/ssh/sshd_config (ClientAliveInterval = 600 / ClientAliveCountMax = 0).\nTogether, these controls ensure all management sessions automatically close after 10 minutes of inactivity, and runtime connections terminate when their processes end."},{"group_id_src":"V-233114","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233114","title":"SRG-APP-000211","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233114","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must separate user functionality (including user interface services) from information system management functionality.","rule_id_src":"SV-233114r961095_rule","rule_id":"SV-233114r961095","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000211-CTR-000530","rule_title":"The container platform must separate user functionality (including user interface services) from information system management functionality.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform and its components to separate management and user functionality.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if management functionality is separated from user functionality. \n\nValidate that the separation is also implemented within the components by trying to execute management functions for each component as a user. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to separate management and user functionality or if component management and user functionality are not separated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Separating user functionality from management functionality is a requirement for all the components within the container platform. Without the separation, users may have access to management functions that can degrade the container platform and the services being offered and can offer a method to bypass testing and validation of functions before introduced into a production environment.\n\nThe separation should be enforced by each component within the container platform.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001082"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"d1b9e6ba-2984-4435-9ae3-16214755b11c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 with Podman inherently separates user and management functionality.\nContainer management actions (e.g., configuration and runtime changes) require administrative privileges, while normal users may only execute containers in rootless mode within their own namespaces.\nPodman’s architecture has no central daemon, preventing non‑admin users from accessing or modifying global container runtime settings.\nSELinux and Linux permissions further ensure only authorized administrators can manage platform functions."},{"group_id_src":"V-233118","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233118","title":"SRG-APP-000219","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233118","severity":"high","group_title":"The container platform must protect authenticity of communications sessions with the use of FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 security requirements for cryptographic modules.","rule_id_src":"SV-233118r1043178_rule","rule_id":"SV-233118r1043178","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000219-CTR-000550","rule_title":"The container platform must protect authenticity of communications sessions with the use of FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 security requirements for cryptographic modules.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 cryptographic modules to protect container images during transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 cryptographic modules are being used to protect container images during transmission. \n\nIf FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 cryptographic modules are not being use, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform is responsible for pulling images from trusted sources and placing those images into its registry. To protect the transmission of images, the container platform must use FIPS-validated 140-2 or 140-3 cryptographic modules. This added protection defends against main-in-the-middle attacks where malicious code could be added to an image during transmission.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001184"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"f6a29b31-ba3d-46b3-aff3-9244e256ee27","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"Podman is FIPS compliant\nonly when the host system is in FIPS mode and other security requirements are met, as Podman itself does not provide FIPS compliance but relies on the host's FIPS-validated cryptographic modules\n\n[admin@mirhel9 ~]$ fips-mode-setup --check\nFIPS mode is enabled.\n[admin@mirhel9 ~]$","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not host container registries itself. when it pulls containers it uses fips compliant modules due to the host having fips enabled. \n\n\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233122","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233122","title":"SRG-APP-000225","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233122","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must fail to a secure state if system initialization fails, shutdown fails, or aborts fail.","rule_id_src":"SV-233122r961122_rule","rule_id":"SV-233122r961122","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000225-CTR-000570","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must fail to a secure state if system initialization fails, shutdown fails, or aborts fail.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform runtime to fail to a secure state if system initialization fails, shutdown fails, or aborts fail.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform runtime fails to a secure state if system initialization fails, shutdown fails, or aborts fail. \n\nIf the container platform runtime cannot be configured to fail securely, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform offers services for container image orchestration and services for users. If any of these services were to fail into an insecure state, security measures for user and data separation and image instantiation could become absent. In addition, audit log protections could be relaxed allowing for investigation of what occurred could be lost. To protect services and data, it is important for the container platform to fail to a secure state if the container platform registry initialization fails, shutdown fails, or aborts fail.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001190"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"680cbe82-af90-4db2-9f63-82bc06e491c8","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman on RHEL 9 is daemonless and inherits secure startup and shutdown behavior directly from the underlying operating system and systemd service controls. If initialization fails, Podman exits with a non‑zero status and does not instantiate containers—leaving no running workloads or configuration changes. Container data and images remain confined under SELinux enforcement, and failed system services (Podman socket, journald, auditd) fail closed, preserving log integrity and preventing unauthorized access. During shutdown or abort events, Podman containers are terminated according to systemd’s service dependency order, ensuring all processes stop and file systems are cleanly unmounted. This architecture ensures Podman fails to a secure state upon initialization or termination failures."},{"group_id_src":"V-233123","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233123","title":"SRG-APP-000226","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233123","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must preserve any information necessary to determine the cause of the disruption or failure.","rule_id_src":"SV-233123r961125_rule","rule_id":"SV-233123r961125","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000226-CTR-000575","rule_title":"The container platform must preserve any information necessary to determine the cause of the disruption or failure.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to preserve information necessary to determine the cause of the disruption or failure.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if information necessary to determine the cause of a disruption or failure is preserved. \n\nIf the information is not preserved, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When a failure occurs within the container platform, preserving the state of the container platform and its components, along with other container services, helps to facilitate container platform restart and return to the operational mode of the organization with less disruption to mission essential processes. When preserving state, considerations for preservation of data confidentiality and integrity must be taken into consideration.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001665"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"919f6195-6ab5-4095-8add-1609749d2693","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 with Podman preserves diagnostic information needed to determine the cause of runtime disruptions or failures through integrated logging, journaling, and container metadata retention.\nPodman writes container lifecycle events and errors to journald and retains per‑container logs under /var/lib/containers/storage/overlay-containers/<id>/userdata/ctr.log. These logs capture container start, stop, and failure messages.\nThe host’s systemd‑journald service provides persistent storage of runtime and kernel events, while auditd logs privileged actions that might have contributed to disruptions.\nThis configuration enables administrators to reconstruct the sequence of events leading to a failure without exposing container data\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233125","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233125","title":"SRG-APP-000233","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233125","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must isolate security functions from non-security functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233125r961131_rule","rule_id":"SV-233125r961131","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000233-CTR-000585","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must isolate security functions from non-security functions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform runtime to isolate security functions from non-security functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify container platform runtime configuration settings to determine whether container services used for security functions are located in an isolated security function such as a separate environment variables, labels, network segregation, and kernel groups.\n\nIf security-related functions are not separate, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform runtime must be configured to isolate those services used for security functions from those used for non-security functions. This separation can be performed using environment variables, labels, network segregation, and kernel groups.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001084"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"aed0906a-f99d-4f4f-8f28-d9997eed4234","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 with Podman isolates security‑related functions from non‑security workloads using kernel‑level mechanisms and container runtime controls.\nSecurity functions such as auditing, logging, and image verification run in separate processes and SELinux domains (container_runtime_t, container_t) from user containers.\nEach container operates in its own namespace and cgroup, ensuring network, kernel, and resource segregation.\nAdministrators further separate sensitive workloads through Podman labels, dedicated CNI networks, and environment variables.\nThis configuration meets the requirement to isolate security and non‑security functions within the container runtime."},{"group_id_src":"V-233126","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233126","title":"SRG-APP-000234","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233126","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must never automatically remove or disable emergency accounts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233126r971528_rule","rule_id":"SV-233126r971528","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000234-CTR-000590","rule_title":"The container platform must never automatically remove or disable emergency accounts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to never remove or disable emergency accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to determine if emergency accounts are automatically removed or disabled. \n\nIf emergency accounts are automatically removed or disabled, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Emergency accounts are administrator accounts that are established in response to crisis situations where the need for rapid account activation is required. Therefore, emergency account activation may bypass normal account authorization processes. If these accounts are automatically disabled, system maintenance during emergencies may not be possible, thus adversely affecting system availability.\n\nEmergency accounts are different from infrequently used accounts (i.e., local logon accounts used by system administrators when network or normal logon/access is not available). Infrequently used accounts also remain available and are not subject to automatic termination dates. However, an emergency account is normally a different account that is created for use by vendors or system maintainers.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001682"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b39746e8-d4b4-44c8-959c-cbe408c162ba","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233127","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233127","title":"SRG-APP-000243","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233127","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prohibit containers from accessing privileged resources.","rule_id_src":"SV-233127r961149_rule","rule_id":"SV-233127r961149","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000243-CTR-000595","rule_title":"The container platform must prohibit containers from accessing privileged resources.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to block instantiation of containers requesting access to host system-privileged resources.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform disallows instantiation of containers trying to access host system privileged resources. \n\nIf the container platform does not block containers requesting host system privileged resources, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Containers images instantiated within the container platform may request access to host system resources. Access to privileged resources can allow for unauthorized and unintended transfer of information, but in some cases, these resources may be needed for the service being offered by the container. By default, containers should be denied instantiation when privileged system resources are requested and granted only after approval has been given.\n\nWhen access to privileged resources is necessary for a container, a new policy for execution should be written for the container. The default behavior must not give containers privileged access to host system resources.\n\nExamples of system resources that should be protected are kernel namespaces and host system sensitive directories such as /etc and /usr.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001090"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"aeb5377e-4f98-4281-9409-65b6be9c5622","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 with rootless Podman prohibits containers from accessing host‑level privileged resources by default.\nRootless containers run without real root privileges, operate in isolated user namespaces, and cannot directly access sensitive host paths such as /etc, /usr, or kernel devices.\nAdditional protections are provided by SELinux confinement, seccomp syscall filtering, and cgroups v2 resource isolation."},{"group_id_src":"V-233128","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233128","title":"SRG-APP-000243","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233128","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prevent unauthorized and unintended information transfer via shared system resources.","rule_id_src":"SV-233128r961149_rule","rule_id":"SV-233128r961149","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000243-CTR-000600","rule_title":"The container platform must prevent unauthorized and unintended information transfer via shared system resources.","fix_text":"Deploy a container platform capable of effectively protecting the resources of one process or user from unauthorized access by another user or process. Configure the container platform to effectively protect the resources of one process or user from unauthorized access by another user or process. The container security solution should help the user understand where the code in the environment was deployed from, and provide controls that prevent deployment from untrusted sources or registries.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform architecture documentation to find out if and how it protects the resources of one process or user (such as working memory, storage, host system kernel, network connections) from unauthorized access by another user or process. \n\nIf the container platform configuration settings do not effectively implement these protections to prevent unauthorized access by another user or process, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform makes host system resources available to container services. These shared resources, such as the host system kernel, network connections, and storage, must be protected to prevent unauthorized and unintended information transfer. The protections must be implemented for users and processes acting on behalf of users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001090"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"e08f7ec6-5c97-4d55-85bb-d04df18309b7","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 with Podman enforces strict container isolation through Linux namespaces, cgroups v2, SELinux, and seccomp. Each container has its own network, process, and memory space, preventing one container from accessing or transferring data to another or the host. Rootless mode further limits privilege, ensuring system resources and user data remain isolated and protected from unauthorized or unintended transfer."},{"group_id_src":"V-233129","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233129","title":"SRG-APP-000246","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233129","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must restrict individuals' ability to launch organizationally defined denial-of-service (DoS) attacks against other information systems.","rule_id_src":"SV-233129r961152_rule","rule_id":"SV-233129r961152","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000246-CTR-000605","rule_title":"The container platform must restrict individuals' ability to launch organizationally defined denial-of-service (DoS) attacks against other information systems.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to restrict the ability of users or other systems to launch DoS attacks from the container platform components by setting resource quotas on resources such as memory, storage, and CPU utilization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform implementation and security documentation and components settings to determine if the information system restricts the ability of users or systems to launch organization-defined DoS attacks against other information systems or networks from the container platform. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to restrict this ability, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform will offer services to users and these services share resources available on the hosting system. To share the resources in a manner that does not exhaust or over utilize resources, it is necessary for the container platform to have mechanisms that allow developers to size there containers to provide minimum and maximum amounts. If there is no mechanism to specify limits, container services can cause DoS by over utilization.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001094"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"23f264a4-ad4e-42a4-9317-4750be367bd8","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"cat /etc/containers/containers.conf\n[containers]\ndefault_ulimits = [\n  \"nofile=1024:2048\",\n  \"nproc=1024:2048\"\n]\ncpus = 2.0\nmemory = \"4096m\"\npids_limit = 100\n\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has this ability, and it is configured."},{"group_id_src":"V-233133","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233133","title":"SRG-APP-000266","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233133","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate error messages that provide information necessary for corrective actions without revealing information that could be exploited by adversaries.","rule_id_src":"SV-233133r961167_rule","rule_id":"SV-233133r961167","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000266-CTR-000625","rule_title":"The container platform must generate error messages that provide information necessary for corrective actions without revealing information that could be exploited by adversaries.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to not write sensitive information into the logs and administrative messages.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and logs to determine if the container platform writes sensitive information such as passwords or private keys into the logs and administrative messages. \n\nIf the container platform writes sensitive or potentially harmful information into the logs and administrative messages, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform is responsible for offering services to users. These services could be across diverse user groups and data types. To protect information about the container platform, services, users, and data, it is important during error message generation to offer enough information to diagnose the error, but not reveal information that needs to be protected.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001312"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"abace040-77a8-412e-8173-3cd031c8ba3c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman messages do not contain sensitive information. "},{"group_id_src":"V-233142","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233142","title":"SRG-APP-000290","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233142","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","rule_id_src":"SV-233142r961206_rule","rule_id":"SV-233142r961206","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000290-CTR-000670","rule_title":"The container platform must use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use cryptographic mechanisms to protect the integrity of audit tools.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the integrity of the audit tools is protected using cryptographic mechanisms. \n\nIf audit tools are not protected through cryptographic mechanisms, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Protecting the integrity of the tools used for auditing purposes is a critical step to ensuring the integrity of audit data. Audit data includes all information (e.g., audit records, audit settings, and audit reports) needed to successfully audit information system activity.\n\nAudit tools include, but are not limited to, vendor provided and open source audit tools needed to successfully view and manipulate audit information system activity and records. Audit tools include custom queries and report generators.\n\nIt is common for attackers to replace the audit tools or inject code into the existing tools with the purpose of providing the capability to hide or erase system activity from the audit logs.\n\nTo address this risk, audit tools must be cryptographically signed in order to provide the capability to identify when the audit tools have been modified, manipulated, or replaced. An example is a checksum hash of the file or files.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001496"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"862f34fa-4606-4321-88d6-3a58ab308780","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233143","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233143","title":"SRG-APP-000291","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233143","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators (SAs) and the information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are created.","rule_id_src":"SV-233143r981871_rule","rule_id":"SV-233143r981871","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000291-CTR-000675","rule_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators (SAs) and the information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are created.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to notify SAs and ISSO when accounts are created.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if system administrators and ISSO are notified when accounts are created. \n\nIf SAs and ISSO are not notified, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to an application, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of re-establishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply create a new account. Sending notification of account creation events to the SA and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to offload those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"6bbed139-aaa7-4ca6-83b9-ce7846704aec","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233144","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233144","title":"SRG-APP-000292","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233144","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators (SAs) and the information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are modified.","rule_id_src":"SV-233144r981872_rule","rule_id":"SV-233144r981872","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000292-CTR-000680","rule_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators (SAs) and the information system security officer (ISSO) when accounts are modified.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to notify system administrators and ISSO when accounts are modified.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if system administrators and ISSO are notified when accounts are modified. \n\nIf system administrators and ISSO are not notified, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When application accounts are modified, user accessibility is affected. Accounts are utilized for identifying individual users or for identifying the application processes themselves. Sending notification of account modification events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that application accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many operating systems can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"1eb3dd17-4526-4ed3-820a-b294c27b2260","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233145","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233145","title":"SRG-APP-000293","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233145","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators and ISSO for account disabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233145r981873_rule","rule_id":"SV-233145r981873","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000293-CTR-000685","rule_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators and ISSO for account disabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to notify system administrators and ISSO when accounts are disabled.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if system administrators and ISSO are notified when accounts are disabled. \n\nIf system administrators and ISSO are not notified, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When application accounts are disabled, user accessibility is affected. Accounts are utilized for identifying individual users or for identifying the application processes themselves. Sending notification of account disabling events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that application accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many operating systems can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"037117da-fb49-4abe-95b4-7ba0acf1f1a6","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233146","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233146","title":"SRG-APP-000294","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233146","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators and ISSO for account removal actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233146r981874_rule","rule_id":"SV-233146r981874","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000294-CTR-000690","rule_title":"The container platform must notify system administrators and ISSO for account removal actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to notify system administrators and ISSO when accounts are removed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if system administrators and ISSO are notified when accounts are removed. \n\nIf system administrators and ISSO are not notified, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"When application accounts are removed, user accessibility is affected. Accounts are utilized for identifying users or for identifying the application processes themselves. Sending notification of account removal events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that application accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time, and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many operating systems can be integrated with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7d3af618-0e9d-43dc-a685-5e4df219add9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. it runs as whatever user runs it. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233149","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233149","title":"SRG-APP-000297","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233149","severity":"low","group_title":"Access to the container platform must display an explicit logout message to user indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communication sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233149r961227_rule","rule_id":"SV-233149r961227","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000297-CTR-000705","rule_title":"Access to the container platform must display an explicit logout message to user indicating the reliable termination of authenticated communication sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform components to display an explicit logout message to users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration settings to determine if the container platform displays a logout message. \n\nIf the container platform does not display a logout message, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Access to the container platform will occur through web and terminal sessions. Any web interfaces must conform to application and web security requirements. Terminal access to the container platform and its components must provide a logout facility that terminates the connection to the component or the platform.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002364"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"83bb19ff-9992-4b4e-ad3a-6cf05af64cf9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe podman container platform has no user interface, it runs as a normal user command, therefore there is not a login or logout function to tie a logout message into"},{"group_id_src":"V-233155","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233155","title":"SRG-APP-000317","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233155","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must terminate shared/group account credentials when members leave the group.","rule_id_src":"SV-233155r981875_rule","rule_id":"SV-233155r981875","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000317-CTR-000735","rule_title":"The container platform must terminate shared/group account credentials when members leave the group.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to terminate shared/group account credentials when members leave the group.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the container platform is configured to terminate shared/group account credentials when members leave the group. \n\nIf the container platform does not terminated shared/group account credentials when members leave the group, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If shared/group account credentials are not terminated when individuals leave the group, the user that left the group can still gain access even though they are no longer authorized. A shared/group account credential is a shared form of authentication that allows multiple individuals to access the application using a single account. There may also be instances when specific user actions need to be performed on the information system without unique user identification or authentication. Examples of credentials include passwords and group membership certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004045"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"efa7be59-4ba5-4a95-8bce-5c8ab2568fb6","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. it runs as whatever user runs it. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233157","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233157","title":"SRG-APP-000319","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233157","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account-enabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233157r961290_rule","rule_id":"SV-233157r961290","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000319-CTR-000745","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically audit account-enabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically audit account-enabling actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the container platform is configured to automatically audit account-enabling actions. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to automatically audit account-enabling actions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to an application, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of re-establishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply enable a new or disabled account. Automatically auditing account enabling actions provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to off-load those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002130"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bcfaee95-227f-4d3e-be5c-48254dd61500","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. it runs as whatever user runs it. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233158","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233158","title":"SRG-APP-000320","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233158","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) of account enabling actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233158r981878_rule","rule_id":"SV-233158r981878","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000320-CTR-000750","rule_title":"The container platform must notify the system administrator (SA) and information system security officer (ISSO) of account enabling actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to notify the SA and ISSO of account enabling actions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the container platform is configured to notify system administrator and ISSO of account enabling actions.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to notify the SA and ISSO of account enabling actions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Once an attacker establishes access to an application, the attacker often attempts to create a persistent method of re-establishing access. One way to accomplish this is for the attacker to simply enable a new or disabled account. Sending notification of account enabling events to the system administrator and ISSO is one method for mitigating this risk. Such a capability greatly reduces the risk that application accessibility will be negatively affected for extended periods of time and provides logging that can be used for forensic purposes.\n\nTo detect and respond to events that affect user accessibility and application processing, applications must notify the appropriate individuals so they can investigate the event.\n\nTo address access requirements, many application developers choose to integrate their applications with enterprise-level authentication/access/auditing mechanisms that meet or exceed access control policy requirements. Such integration allows the application developer to offload those access control functions and focus on core application features and functionality.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000015"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2013f03e-5442-42e3-a5e9-e863e11ef079","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no ability to do this due to podman not having any account or identity functionality. it runs as whatever user runs it. Therefore this not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233162","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233162","title":"SRG-APP-000340","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233162","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","rule_id_src":"SV-233162r961353_rule","rule_id":"SV-233162r961353","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000340-CTR-000770","rule_title":"The container platform must prevent non-privileged users from executing privileged functions to include disabling, circumventing, or altering implemented security safeguards/countermeasures.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to security to protect all privileged functionality. Assigning roles that limit what actions a particular user can perform are the most common means of meeting this requirement.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation to obtain the definition of the container platform functionality considered privileged in the context of the information system in question. \n\nReview the container platform security configuration and/or other means used to protect privileged functionality from unauthorized use. \n\nIf the configuration does not protect all of the actions defined as privileged, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling what users can perform privileged functions prevents unauthorized users from performing tasks that may expose data or degrade the container platform. When users are not segregated into privileged and non-privileged users, unauthorized individuals may perform tasks such as deploying containers, pulling images into the register, and modify keys in the keystore. These actions can introduce malicious containers and cause denial-of-service (DoS) attacks and undermine the container platform integrity. The enforcement may take place at the container platform and can be implemented within each container platform component (e.g. runtime, registry, and keystore).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002235"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bd9bcbf3-d168-4b71-8945-4b8a70f09506","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not support roles, or elevated account actions. it all runs under what ever user executed the command. this is therefore not a finding"},{"group_id_src":"V-233163","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233163","title":"SRG-APP-000342","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233163","severity":"medium","group_title":"Container images instantiated by the container platform must execute using least privileges.","rule_id_src":"SV-233163r961359_rule","rule_id":"SV-233163r961359","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000342-CTR-000775","rule_title":"Container images instantiated by the container platform must execute using least privileges.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to block instantiation with no more privileges than necessary.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform disallows instantiation of containers trying to execute with more privileges than required or with privileged permissions. \n\nIf the container platform does not block containers requesting privileged permissions, privilege escalation, or allows containers to have more privileges than required, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Containers running within the container platform must execute as non-privileged. When a container can execute as a privileged container, the privileged container is also a privileged user within the hosting system, and the hosting system becomes a major security risk. It is important for the container platform runtime to validate the container user and disallow instantiation if the container is trying to execute with more privileges than required, as a privileged user, or is trying to perform a privilege escalation.\n\nWhen privileged access is necessary for a container, a new policy for execution should be written for the container. The default behavior must not give containers privileged execution.\n\nExamples of privileged users are root, admin, and default service accounts for the container platform.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002233"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ff96755d-91f0-4693-9930-5a3452967520","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman runs instantiation as the current user and does not provide facilities to elevate or change users."},{"group_id_src":"V-233164","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233164","title":"SRG-APP-000343","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233164","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must audit the execution of privileged functions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233164r961362_rule","rule_id":"SV-233164r961362","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000343-CTR-000780","rule_title":"The container platform must audit the execution of privileged functions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to log privileged activity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation and log configuration to verify the application server logs privileged activity. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to log privileged activity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Privileged functions within the container platform can be component specific or can envelope the entire container platform. Because of the nature of the commands, it is important to understand what command was executed for either investigation of an incident or for debugging/error correction; therefore, privileged function execution must be audited.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002234"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"1b9fdb6d-eefd-4ff9-92ab-e1be1ee2c6b5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not have this ability, however the host auditd logs all access to all files, as well as sudo and su activity."},{"group_id_src":"V-233165","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233165","title":"SRG-APP-000345","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233165","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful login attempts in 15 minutes are exceeded.","rule_id_src":"SV-233165r961368_rule","rule_id":"SV-233165r961368","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000345-CTR-000785","rule_title":"The container platform must automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful login attempts in 15 minutes are exceeded.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful login attempts in 15 minutes are exceeded.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Determine if the container platform is configured to automatically lock an account until the locked account is released by an administrator when three unsuccessful login attempts in 15 minutes are exceeded. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to lock the account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"By limiting the number of failed login attempts, the risk of unauthorized system access via user password guessing, otherwise known as brute forcing, is reduced. Limits are imposed by locking the account.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002238"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bfbc220e-78f3-4010-9db6-0c077bde2c2c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman doesnt handle account management. however the host is configured to lock accounts after 3 failed attempts"},{"group_id_src":"V-233166","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233166","title":"SRG-APP-000516","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233166","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide the configuration for organization-identified individuals or roles to change the auditing to be performed on all components, based on all selectable event criteria within organization-defined time thresholds.","rule_id_src":"SV-233166r961863_rule","rule_id":"SV-233166r961863","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000516-CTR-000790","rule_title":"The container platform must provide the configuration for organization-identified individuals or roles to change the auditing to be performed on all components, based on all selectable event criteria within organization-defined time thresholds.","fix_text":"Deploy a container platform that provides the ability for users in authorized roles to reconfigure auditing at any time. Deploy a container platform that allows audit configuration changes to take effect within the timeframe required by the organization and without involving actions or events that the organization rules unacceptable.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration setting. \n\nIf the container platform does not provide the ability for users in authorized roles to reconfigure auditing at any time of the user's choosing, this is a finding. \n\nIf changes in audit configuration cannot take effect until after a certain time or date, or until some event, such as a server restart, has occurred, and if that time or event does not meet the requirements specified by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Auditing requirements may change per organization or situation within and organization. With the container platform allowing an organization to customize the auditing, an organization can decide to extend or limit auditing as necessary to meet organizational requirements. Auditing that is limited to conserve resources may be extended to address certain threat situations. In addition, auditing may be limited to a specific set of events to facilitate audit reduction, analysis, and reporting. Organizations can establish time thresholds in which audit actions are changed, for example, near real-time, within minutes, or within hours.\r\n\r\nModifying auditing within the container platform must be controlled to only those individuals or roles identified by the organization to modify auditable events.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000366"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"797fde06-7319-4199-a284-7737c22a52ec","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not have ability to affect auditing. this is not applicable"},{"group_id_src":"V-233168","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233168","title":"SRG-APP-000357","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233168","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must allocate audit record storage capacity in accordance with organization-defined audit record storage requirements.","rule_id_src":"SV-233168r961392_rule","rule_id":"SV-233168r961392","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000357-CTR-000800","rule_title":"The container platform must allocate audit record storage capacity in accordance with organization-defined audit record storage requirements.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to allocate audit record storage capacity in accordance with organization-defined audit record storage requirements.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if audit record storage capacity is allocated in accordance with organization-defined audit record storage requirements. \n\nIf audit record storage capacity is not allocated in accordance with organization-defined audit record storage requirements, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"In order to ensure applications have a sufficient storage capacity in which to write the audit logs, applications need to be able to allocate audit record storage capacity.\n\nThe task of allocating audit record storage capacity is usually performed during initial installation of the application and is closely associated with the DBA and system administrator roles. The DBA or system administrator will usually coordinate the allocation of physical drive space with the application owner/installer and the application will prompt the installer to provide the capacity information, the physical location of the disk, or both.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001849"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5aba736f-5b62-44db-b9ee-b04ff6347f0a","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-podman does not perform this type of auditing. However the host has a defined audit log partition and logs are sent off host to another server"},{"group_id_src":"V-233169","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233169","title":"SRG-APP-000358","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233169","severity":"medium","group_title":"Audit records must be stored at a secondary location.","rule_id_src":"SV-233169r961395_rule","rule_id":"SV-233169r961395","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000358-CTR-000805","rule_title":"Audit records must be stored at a secondary location.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to off-load the logs to a remote log or management server.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the log records are being off-loaded to a separate system or transferred from the container platform storage location to a storage location other than the container platform itself. \n\nThe information system may demonstrate this capability using a log management application, system configuration, or other means. \n\nIf logs are not being off-loaded, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Auditable events are used in the investigation of incidents and must be protected from being deleted or altered. Often, events that took place in the past must be viewed to understand the entire incident. For the purposes of audit event protection and recall, audit events are often off-loaded to an external storage location. The container platform must provide a mechanism to assist in the off-loading of the audit data or at a minimum, must not hinder an external process used for audit event off-loading.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001851"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7929bb22-96b7-4d21-8445-6b65a1cd1691","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthis is not a function of podman, but the host does send its logs to a centralized remote log server"},{"group_id_src":"V-233170","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233170","title":"SRG-APP-000359","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233170","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","rule_id_src":"SV-233170r961398_rule","rule_id":"SV-233170r961398","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000359-CTR-000810","rule_title":"The container platform must provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of repository maximum audit record storage capacity.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it is configured to provide an immediate warning to the SA and ISSO (at a minimum) when allocated audit record storage volume reaches 75 percent of repository maximum audit record storage capacity. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to provide an immediate real-time alert, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If security personnel are not notified immediately upon storage volume utilization reaching 75 percent, they are unable to plan for storage capacity expansion.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001855"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"652c120a-5d93-4ba1-99ac-494de6498fb6","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not perform this type of auditing. However the host does and logs are sent to a central server to allow for alerting and scanning. additionally, the host is set to halt if there is an audit failure."},{"group_id_src":"V-233171","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233171","title":"SRG-APP-000360","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233171","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","rule_id_src":"SV-233171r961401_rule","rule_id":"SV-233171r961401","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000360-CTR-000815","rule_title":"The container platform must provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO, at a minimum, of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if it is configured to provide an immediate real-time alert to the SA and ISSO of all audit failure events requiring real-time alerts. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to provide an immediate real-time alert, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"It is critical for the appropriate personnel to be aware if a system is at risk of failing to process audit logs as required. Without a real-time alert, security personnel may be unaware of an impending failure of the audit capability and system operation may be adversely affected.\n\nAlerts provide organizations with urgent messages. Real-time alerts provide these messages immediately (i.e., the time from event detection to alert occurs in seconds or less).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001858"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5cbd4cdd-f4bc-481d-bca9-00c419e13fa9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not perform this type of auditing. However the host does and logs are sent to a central server to allow for alerting and scanning. additionally, the host is set to halt if there is an audit failure."},{"group_id_src":"V-233181","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233181","title":"SRG-APP-000374","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233181","severity":"medium","group_title":"All audit records must use UTC or GMT time stamps.","rule_id_src":"SV-233181r961443_rule","rule_id":"SV-233181r961443","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000374-CTR-000865","rule_title":"All audit records must use UTC or GMT time stamps.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use UTC or GMT or local time that offset from UTC based time stamps for log records.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform documentation and configuration files to determine if time stamps for log records can be mapped to UTC or GMT or local time that offsets from UTC. \n\nIf the time stamp cannot be mapped to UTC or GMT, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform and its components must generate audit records using either Coordinated Universal Time (UTC) or Greenwich Mean Time (GMT) time stamps or local time that offset from UTC. All the components must use the same standard so that the events can be tied together to understand what took place within the overall container platform.\n\nTime stamps generated by the container platform and its components must include date and time.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001890"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"8d7dc99d-e1cf-4f7e-9d49-e6463d3ec8ab","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not log in this fasion. however the host auditd does log in UTC timestamps. Therefore marking this as not a finding"},{"group_id_src":"V-233182","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233182","title":"SRG-APP-000375","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233182","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must record time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.","rule_id_src":"SV-233182r961446_rule","rule_id":"SV-233182r961446","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000375-CTR-000870","rule_title":"The container platform must record time stamps for audit records that meet a granularity of one second for a minimum degree of precision.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to use time stamps for log records that can meet a granularity of one second.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform documentation and configuration files to determine if time stamps for log records meet a granularity of one second. \n\nIf the time stamp cannot generate to a one-second granularity, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To properly investigate an event, it is important to have enough granularity within the time stamps to determine the chronological order of the audited events. Without this granularity, events may be interpreted out of proper sequence, thus hobbling the investigation or causing the investigation to come to inaccurate conclusions.\n\nTime stamps generated by the container platform include date and time. Granularity of time measurements refers to the degree of synchronization between information system clocks and reference clocks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001889"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"151c9526-d8e1-4e7f-b198-3c9bb873e830","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not have an audit function. However the host does and it is down to the microsecond. marking this as not a finding."},{"group_id_src":"V-233184","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233184","title":"SRG-APP-000378","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233184","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prohibit the installation of patches and updates without explicit privileged status.","rule_id_src":"SV-233184r981884_rule","rule_id":"SV-233184r981884","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000378-CTR-000880","rule_title":"The container platform must prohibit the installation of patches and updates without explicit privileged status.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to only allow patch installation and upgrades using privileged accounts.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if patches and updates can only be installed through accounts with privileged status. \n\nAttempt to install a patch or upgrade using a nonprivileged user account. \n\nIf patches or updates can be installed using a nonprivileged account or the container platform is not configured to stop the installation using a nonprivileged account, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling access to those users and roles responsible for patching and updating the container platform reduces the risk of untested or potentially malicious software from being installed within the platform. This access may be separate from the access required to install container images into the registry and those access requirements required to instantiate an image into a service. Explicit privileges (escalated or administrative privileges) provide the regular user with explicit capabilities and control that exceeds the rights of a regular user.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003980"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3437c12d-8573-4245-bfb0-d76a2dbb7ef9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npatching of the podman binaries can only be done by root user. this is not a function of podman but rather of the host OS itself. This is therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233185","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233185","title":"SRG-APP-000378","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233185","severity":"high","group_title":"The container platform runtime must prohibit the instantiation of container images without explicit privileged status.","rule_id_src":"SV-233185r981885_rule","rule_id":"SV-233185r981885","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000378-CTR-000885","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must prohibit the instantiation of container images without explicit privileged status.","fix_text":" Configure the container platform runtime to prohibit the instantiation of container images without explicit container image instantiation privileges given to users.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform runtime configuration to determine if only accounts given specific container instantiation privileges can execute the container image instantiation process. \n\nAttempt to instantiate a container image using an account that does not have the proper privileges to execute the process. \n\nIf container images can be instantiated using an account without the proper privileges, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling access to those users and roles responsible for container image instantiation reduces the risk of untested or potentially malicious containers from being executed within the platform and on the hosting system. This access may be separate from the access required to install container images into the registry and those access requirements required to perform patch management and upgrades within the container platform. Explicit privileges (escalated or administrative privileges) provide the regular user with explicit capabilities and control that exceeds the rights of a regular user.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003980"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b41d7593-2a0a-4879-b0a9-9df72e79774a","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"[root@mirhel9 ~]# ll /usr/bin/podman\n-rwxr-x---. 1 root container-admins 52475488 Jun 25 10:45 /usr/bin/podman\n[root@mirhel9 ~]#\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is handled by linux group membership, if your not in the group named container-admins you cannot run a podman binary\n\n\n[miadmin@mirhel9 ~]$ podman\n-bash: /usr/bin/podman: Permission denied\n[miadmin@mirhel9 ~]$\n\n\n\n\n\n[miadmin@mirhel9 ~]$ podman\n-bash: /usr/bin/podman: Permission denied\n[miadmin@mirhel9 ~]$\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233186","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233186","title":"SRG-APP-000378","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233186","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform registry must prohibit installation or modification of container images without explicit privileged status.","rule_id_src":"SV-233186r981888_rule","rule_id":"SV-233186r981888","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000378-CTR-000890","rule_title":"The container platform registry must prohibit installation or modification of container images without explicit privileged status.","fix_text":"Document and obtain approval for any nonadministrative users who require the ability to create, alter, or replace container images within the container platform registry. Implement the approved permissions. Revoke any unapproved permissions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform registry security settings with respect to nonadministrative users' ability to create, alter, or replace container images. \n\nIf any such permissions exist and are not documented and approved, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling access to those users and roles that perform container platform registry functions reduces the risk of untested or potentially malicious containers from being introduced into the platform. This access may be separate from the access required to instantiate container images into services and those access requirements required to perform patch management and upgrades within the container platform. Explicit privileges (escalated or administrative privileges) provide the regular user with explicit capabilities and control that exceeds the rights of a regular user.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003980"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"59e69d47-096a-489f-b28e-e725722cf9a3","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not offer a container registry. "},{"group_id_src":"V-233188","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233188","title":"SRG-APP-000380","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233188","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce access restrictions for container platform configuration changes.","rule_id_src":"SV-233188r961461_rule","rule_id":"SV-233188r961461","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000380-CTR-000900","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce access restrictions for container platform configuration changes.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to enforce access restrictions associated with changes to the container platform components configuration.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration settings to determine if the container platform enforces access restrictions associated with changes to container platform components configuration. \n\nIf the container platform does not enforce such access restrictions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Configuration changes cause the container platform to change the way it operates. These changes can be used to improve the system with added features or performance, but these configuration changes can also be used to introduce malicious features and degrade performance. To control the configuration changes made to the container platform, it is important that only authorized users are allowed, through container platform enforcement, to make configuration changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"2e3dfbb5-a787-4601-ac35-a0457f683ecd","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 host enforces access restrictions on container platform configuration.\nGlobal Podman configuration directories (/etc/containers/) are owned by root and are writable only by administrators.\nRootless Podman users operate under isolated user namespaces without permission to modify global runtime behavior.\nThe Podman binary is restricted via group access (container-users), and audit rules monitor configuration file changes."},{"group_id_src":"V-233189","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233189","title":"SRG-APP-000381","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233189","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must enforce access restrictions and support auditing of the enforcement actions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233189r981889_rule","rule_id":"SV-233189r981889","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000381-CTR-000905","rule_title":"The container platform must enforce access restrictions and support auditing of the enforcement actions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to log the enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation and logs to determine if enforcement actions used to restrict access associated with changes to the container platform are logged. \n\nIf these actions are not logged, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Auditing the enforcement of access restrictions against changes to the container platform helps identify attacks and provides forensic data for investigation for after-the-fact actions. Attempts to change configurations, components, or data maintained by a component (e.g., images in the registry, running containers in the runtime, or keys in the keystore) must be audited. \n\nEnforcement actions are the methods or mechanisms used to prevent unauthorized changes to configuration settings. Enforcement action methods may be as simple as denying access to a file based on the application of file permissions (access restriction). Audit items may consist of lists of actions blocked by access restrictions or changes identified after the fact.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003938"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"0b91042d-03de-496e-8565-2a2e1dd438f9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe host that podman is installed on, audits all file access and changes. This is beyond the scope of the podman application itself however. marking as not a finding since the essence of the stig is still being satisfied by other means."},{"group_id_src":"V-233190","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233190","title":"SRG-APP-000383","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233190","severity":"medium","group_title":"All non-essential, unnecessary, and unsecure DoD ports, protocols, and services must be disabled in the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233190r961470_rule","rule_id":"SV-233190r961470","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000383-CTR-000910","rule_title":"All non-essential, unnecessary, and unsecure DoD ports, protocols, and services must be disabled in the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to only utilize secure ports and protocols required for operation that have been accepted for use as per the Ports, Protocols, and Services Category Assignments List (CAL) from DISA (PPSM).","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if services or capabilities presently on the information system are required for operational or mission needs. \n\nIf additional services or capabilities are present on the system, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To properly offer services to the user and to orchestrate containers, the container platform may offer services that use ports and protocols that best fit those services. The container platform, when offering the services, must only offer the services on ports and protocols authorized by the DoD.\n\nTo validate that the services are using only the approved ports and protocols, the organization must perform a periodic scan/review of the container platform and disable functions, ports, protocols, and services deemed to be unneeded or non-secure.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001762"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"de83e341-d03e-4502-9c62-e72eb8b0f018","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not offer any kind of listeners, daemons, or apis, that would use a port. Therefore this is not applicable"},{"group_id_src":"V-233191","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233191","title":"SRG-APP-000384","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233191","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prevent component execution in accordance with organization-defined policies regarding software program usage and restrictions, and/or rules authorizing the terms and conditions of software program usage.","rule_id_src":"SV-233191r961473_rule","rule_id":"SV-233191r961473","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000384-CTR-000915","rule_title":"The container platform must prevent component execution in accordance with organization-defined policies regarding software program usage and restrictions, and/or rules authorizing the terms and conditions of software program usage.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform so that any platform components that are not required in order to meet the organization's mission are disabled or removed. Document the components that must be disabled or removed for reference.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration setting to determine if policies, rules, or restrictions exist regarding usage of container platform components. \n\nIf no such no restrictions are in place, this is not a finding. \n\nIdentify any components the organization requires to be disabled or removed and configure the container platform according to that policy. \n\nIf the container platform components are not disabled or removed according to the organization's policy, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform may offer components such as DNS services, firewall services, router services, or web services that are not required by every organization to meet their needs. Container platform components may also add capabilities that run counter to the mission or that provide users with functionality that exceeds mission requirements. To meet the requirements of an organization, the container platform must have a method to remove or disable components not required to meet the organization's mission.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001764"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"d14e63f0-5586-447f-836f-ddfed0e24e82","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthere are no podman components required to be disabled by organizational policy"},{"group_id_src":"V-233192","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233192","title":"SRG-APP-000386","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233192","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform registry must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception (whitelist) policy to allow only authorized container images in the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233192r961479_rule","rule_id":"SV-233192r961479","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000386-CTR-000920","rule_title":"The container platform registry must employ a deny-all, permit-by-exception (whitelist) policy to allow only authorized container images in the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to utilize a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy when allowing the execution of authorized software.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration settings to identify if the container platform whitelisting specifies which container platform components are allowed to execute.\n\nCheck for the existence of policy settings or policy files that can be configured to restrict container platform component execution. Demonstrate how the program execution is restricted. Look for a deny-all, permit-by-exception policy of restriction.\n\nSome methods for restricting execution include but are not limited to the use of custom capabilities built into the application or Software Restriction Policies, Application Security Manager, or Role-Based Access Controls (RBAC).\n\nIf container platform whitelisting is not utilized or does not follow a deny-all, permit-by-exception (whitelist) policy, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling the sources where container images can be pulled from allows the organization to define what software can be run within the container platform. Allowing any container image to be introduced and instantiated within the container platform may introduce malicious code and vulnerabilities to the platform and the hosting system. \n\nThe container platform registry must deny all container images except for those signed by organizational-approved sources.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001774"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"71d7a3cf-a000-4aa5-941e-d3048e20c3e5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":" /etc/containers/registries.conf\n\nunqualified-search-registries = [\"gitlab.ogs18.ogs.mi.ds.army.smil.mil:5050\"]\n\n[[registry]]\nlocation = \"gitlab.ogs18.ogs.mi.ds.army.smil.mil:5050\"\ninsecure = true\nblocked = false  \n\n# Deny all other registries\n[[registry]]\nlocation = \"docker.io\"\nblocked = true\n\n[[registry]]\nlocation = \"quay.io\"\nblocked = true\n\n[[registry]]\nlocation = \"ghcr.io\"\nblocked = true","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman configuration files employ a deny all and allow my exception format "},{"group_id_src":"V-233193","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233193","title":"SRG-APP-000389","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233193","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must require users to reauthenticate when organization-defined circumstances or situations require reauthentication.","rule_id_src":"SV-233193r1050787_rule","rule_id":"SV-233193r1050787","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000389-CTR-000925","rule_title":"The container platform must require users to reauthenticate when organization-defined circumstances or situations require reauthentication.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to require a user to reauthenticate when organization-defined circumstances or situations are met.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform requires a user to reauthenticate when organization-defined circumstances or situations are met. \n\nIf the container platform does not meet this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling user access is paramount in securing the container platform. During a user's access to the container platform, events may occur that change the user's access and which require reauthentication. For instance, if the capability to change security roles or escalate privileges is implemented, it is critical the user reauthenticate.\n\nIn addition to the reauthentication requirements associated with change in security roles or privilege escalation, organizations may require reauthentication of individuals in other situations, including (but not limited to) the following circumstances:\n\n(i) When authenticators change; \n(ii) When roles change; \n(iii) When security categories of information systems change; \n(iv) When the execution of privileged functions occurs; \n(v) After a fixed period of time; or\n(vi) Periodically.\n\nWithin the DOD, the minimum circumstances requiring reauthentication are privilege escalation and role changes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002038"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c010d5bc-e64c-4d27-ad20-c21e57b15eb9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe podman command runs as user level execution event. This requires them to login to the machine locally or over ssh. The host itself is the only authentication mechanism, and it has configurations that time the user out, and force password changes regularly according to DOD rhel9 standards"},{"group_id_src":"V-233195","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233195","title":"SRG-APP-000391","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233195","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must be configured to use multi-factor authentication for user authentication.","rule_id_src":"SV-233195r961494_rule","rule_id":"SV-233195r961494","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000391-CTR-000935","rule_title":"The container platform must be configured to use multi-factor authentication for user authentication.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to accept standard DoD multifactor token-based credentials when users interface with the platform.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to ensure the container platform is configured to use an approved DoD multifactor token (CAC) when accessing platform via user interfaces. \n\nIf multifactor authentication is not configured, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling access to the container platform and its components is paramount in having a secure and stable system. Validating users is the first step in controlling the access. Users may be validated by the overall container platform or they may be validated by each component. To standardize and reduce the risks of unauthorized access, the use of multifactor token-based credentials is the preferred method.\n\nDoD has mandated the use of the CAC to support identity management and personal authentication for systems covered under HSPD 12, as well as a primary component of layered protection for national security systems.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001953"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"e414c335-7661-4642-8983-c161b93abdf2","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not handle any authentication or identification subroutines. these are all handled by the host its installed on. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233200","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233200","title":"SRG-APP-000400","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233200","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after an organization-defined time period.","rule_id_src":"SV-233200r961521_rule","rule_id":"SV-233200r961521","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000400-CTR-000960","rule_title":"The container platform must prohibit the use of cached authenticators after an organization-defined time period.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to prohibit the use of cached authenticators after an organization-defined time period.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if the platform is configured to prohibit the use of cached authenticators after an organization-defined time period. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to prohibit the use of cached authenticators after an organization-defined time period, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If cached authentication information is out of date, the validity of the authentication information may be questionable.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002007"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"3458bf0f-7820-40b2-ba45-b3fffe7084e5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not handle any authentication or identification subroutines. these are all handled by the host its installed on. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233201","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233201","title":"SRG-APP-000401","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233201","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform, for PKI-based authentication, must implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","rule_id_src":"SV-233201r981893_rule","rule_id":"SV-233201r981893","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000401-CTR-000965","rule_title":"The container platform, for PKI-based authentication, must implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to implement a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration.\n\n If the container platform is not implemented to use a local cache of revocation data to support path discovery and validation in case of the inability to access revocation information via the network, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The potential of allowing access to users who are no longer authorized  (have revoked certificates) increases unless a local cache of revocation data is configured.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004068"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bd98b6ce-9bf2-4c2b-bc5f-c7c5b7a5023f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not handle any authentication or identification subroutines. these are all handled by the host its installed on. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233202","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233202","title":"SRG-APP-000402","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233202","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must accept Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials from other federal agencies.","rule_id_src":"SV-233202r961527_rule","rule_id":"SV-233202r961527","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000402-CTR-000970","rule_title":"The container platform must accept Personal Identity Verification (PIV) credentials from other federal agencies.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to accept PIV credentials from other federal agencies.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform accepts PIV credentials from other federal agencies. \n\nIf the container platform does not accept other federal agency PIV credentials, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Controlling access to the container platform and its components is paramount in having a secure and stable system. Validating users is the first step in controlling the access. Users may be validated by the overall container platform or they may be validated by each component. It is essential to accept PIV credentials from other federal agencies and eliminate the possibility of access being denied to authorized users.\n\nPIV credentials are those credentials issued by federal agencies that conform to FIPS Publication 201 and supporting guidance documents. OMB Memorandum 11-11 requires federal agencies to continue implementing the requirements specified in HSPD-12 to enable agency-wide use of PIV credentials.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002009"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"39382d1b-e379-437c-a1b9-de36eac4c87c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not handle any authentication or identification subroutines. these are all handled by the host its installed on. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233206","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233206","title":"SRG-APP-000409","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233206","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must audit non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions' organization-defined audit events associated with non-local maintenance.","rule_id_src":"SV-233206r961548_rule","rule_id":"SV-233206r961548","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000409-CTR-000990","rule_title":"The container platform must audit non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions' organization-defined audit events associated with non-local maintenance.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to audit non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions' organization-defined audit events.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform to verify if the platform is auditing non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions' organization-defined audit events. \n\nIf the container platform is not auditing non-local maintenance and diagnostic sessions' organization-defined audit events, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"To fully investigate an attack, it is important to understand the event and those events taking place during the same time period. Often, non-local administrative access and diagnostic sessions are not logged. These events are seen as only administrative functions and not worthy of being audited, but these events are important in any investigation and are a major tool for assessing and investigating attacks.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002884"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"dfc8328b-c7c6-48e4-9d65-eb1c53b6e4c2","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman has no maintenance modes, or diagnostic modes. the host itself has auditing enabled for all file access and changes. However this is outside of the scope of podman, and therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233207","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233207","title":"SRG-APP-000411","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233207","severity":"medium","group_title":"Container platform applications and Application Program Interfaces (API) used for nonlocal maintenance sessions must use FIPS-validated keyed-hash message authentication code (HMAC) to protect the integrity of nonlocal maintenance and diagnostic communications.","rule_id_src":"SV-233207r961554_rule","rule_id":"SV-233207r961554","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000411-CTR-000995","rule_title":"Container platform applications and Application Program Interfaces (API) used for nonlocal maintenance sessions must use FIPS-validated keyed-hash message authentication code (HMAC) to protect the integrity of nonlocal maintenance and diagnostic communications.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform applications and APIs used for nonlocal maintenance sessions to use FIPS-validated HMAC to protect the integrity of nonlocal maintenance and diagnostic communications.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Validate that container platform applications and APIs used for nonlocal maintenance sessions are using FIPS-validated HMAC to protect the integrity of nonlocal maintenance and diagnostic communications. \n\nIf the sessions are not using FIPS-validated HMAC, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Unapproved mechanisms that are used for authentication to the cryptographic module are not verified, and therefore cannot be relied on to provide confidentiality or integrity, and DoD data may be compromised.\r\n\r\nNonlocal maintenance and diagnostic activities are activities conducted by individuals communicating through either an external network (e.g., the internet) or an internal network.\r\n\r\nCurrently, HMAC is the only FIPS-approved algorithm for generating and verifying message/data authentication codes in accordance with FIPS 198-1. Products that are FIPS 140-2 validated will have an HMAC that meets specification; however, the option must be configured for use as the only message authentication code used for authentication to cryptographic modules.\r\n\r\nSeparate requirements for configuring applications and protocols used by each product (e.g., SNMPv3, SSHv2, NTP, and other protocols and applications that require server/client authentication) are required to implement this requirement. The SSHv2 protocol suite must be mandated in the product because it includes layer 7 protocols such as SCP and SFTP that can be used for secure file transfers.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002890"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"c55b8dee-fd2b-4989-a500-ea61e263acee","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not employ any web based management interfaces or API. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233208","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233208","title":"SRG-APP-000412","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233208","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must configure web management tools and Application Program Interfaces (API) with FIPS-validated Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) cipher block algorithm to protect the confidentiality of maintenance and diagnostic communications for nonlocal maintenance sessions.","rule_id_src":"SV-233208r961557_rule","rule_id":"SV-233208r961557","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000412-CTR-001000","rule_title":"The container platform must configure web management tools and Application Program Interfaces (API) with FIPS-validated Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) cipher block algorithm to protect the confidentiality of maintenance and diagnostic communications for nonlocal maintenance sessions.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform web management tools and Application Program Interfaces (API) with FIPS-validated Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) cipher block algorithm to protect the confidentiality of maintenance and diagnostic communications for nonlocal maintenance sessions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Validate the container platform web management tools and Application Program Interfaces (API) are configured to use FIPS-validated Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) cipher block algorithms to protect the confidentiality of maintenance and diagnostic communications for nonlocal maintenance sessions. \n\nIf the web management tools and API are not configured to use FIPS-validated Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) cipher block algorithms, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without confidentiality protection mechanisms, unauthorized individuals may gain access to sensitive information via a remote access session.\r\n\r\nNonlocal maintenance and diagnostic activities are activities conducted by individuals communicating through either an external network (e.g., the internet) or an internal network.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-003123"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"fb2fd571-ec3a-4897-82d2-685056a1586e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not employ any web based management interfaces or API. Therefore this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233210","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233210","title":"SRG-APP-000414","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233210","severity":"medium","group_title":"Vulnerability scanning applications must implement privileged access authorization to all container platform components, containers, and container images for selected organization-defined vulnerability scanning activities.","rule_id_src":"SV-233210r961563_rule","rule_id":"SV-233210r961563","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000414-CTR-001010","rule_title":"Vulnerability scanning applications must implement privileged access authorization to all container platform components, containers, and container images for selected organization-defined vulnerability scanning activities.","fix_text":"Configure the vulnerability scanning application to have privileged access to the container platform components, containers, and container images.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Validate that scanning applications have privileged access to container platform components, containers, and container images to properly perform vulnerability scans. \n\nIf privileged access is not given to the scanning application, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"In certain situations, the nature of the vulnerability scanning may be more intrusive, or the container platform component that is the subject of the scanning may contain highly sensitive information. Privileged access authorization to selected system components facilitates more thorough vulnerability scanning and protects the sensitive nature of such scanning.\n\nThe vulnerability scanning application must utilize privileged access authorization for the scanning account.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001067"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"4c5bcdc5-219f-42a7-8a8c-f73258014b15","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nprivileged access is provided to the acas scanner for routine vulnerability scanning."},{"group_id_src":"V-233211","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233211","title":"SRG-APP-000516","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233211","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must implement NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","rule_id_src":"SV-233211r961863_rule","rule_id":"SV-233211r961863","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000416-CTR-001015","rule_title":"The container platform must implement NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information in accordance with applicable federal laws, Executive Orders, directives, policies, regulations, and standards.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to utilize NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified information.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation to verify that the container platform is using NSA-approved cryptography to protect classified data and applications. \n\nIf the container platform is not using NSA-approved cryptography for classified data and applications, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Use of weak or untested encryption algorithms undermines the purposes of utilizing encryption to protect data and images. The container platform must implement cryptographic modules adhering to the higher standards approved by the federal government since this provides assurance they have been tested and validated.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002450"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"6be89fca-aeec-420a-8802-f98a95afbed0","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThe RHEL 9 host running Podman operates in FIPS mode (/proc/sys/crypto/fips_enabled = 1) and enforces the FIPS system crypto policy.\nAll container runtime and registry communications use the system’s FIPS‑validated OpenSSL and GnuTLS modules.\nTLS 1.0/1.1 and SSL 2.0/3.0 are disabled; only TLS 1.2 and 1.3 using NSA‑approved ciphers are permitted."},{"group_id_src":"V-233220","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233220","title":"SRG-APP-000429","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233220","severity":"high","group_title":"The container platform keystore must implement encryption to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information at rest within the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233220r1050650_rule","rule_id":"SV-233220r1050650","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000429-CTR-001060","rule_title":"The container platform keystore must implement encryption to prevent unauthorized disclosure of information at rest within the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform keystore encryption to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information for applicable sensitivity level.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform keystore documentation and configuration to verify encryption levels meet the information sensitivity level. \n\nIf the container platform keystore encryption configuration does not meet system requirements, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Container platform keystore is used for container deployments for persistent storage of all its REST API objects. These objects are sensitive in nature and should be encrypted at rest to avoid any unauthorized disclosure. Selection of a cryptographic mechanism is based on the need to protect the confidentiality of organizational information. The strength of mechanism is commensurate with the security category and/or classification of the information.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002476"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"020074cc-705c-4d9e-af1c-a81f9354f4ef","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthe podman container system runs as a user unlike docker. There is no keystore, and on disk encryption at rest is handled by the netapp. The virtual machine itself and all its disks are stored on the netapp which uses compliant disk encryption"},{"group_id_src":"V-233221","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233221","title":"SRG-APP-000431","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233221","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must maintain separate execution domains for each container by assigning each container a separate address space.","rule_id_src":"SV-233221r961608_rule","rule_id":"SV-233221r961608","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000431-CTR-001065","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must maintain separate execution domains for each container by assigning each container a separate address space.","fix_text":"Deploy a container platform runtime capable of maintaining a separate execution domain and namespace for each executing process. Create a namespace for each containers, defining them as logical groups.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform runtime documentation and configuration is maintaining a separate execution domain for each executing process. Different groups of applications, and services with different security needs, should be deployed in separate namespaces as a first level of isolation. \n\nIf container platform runtime is not configured to execute processes in separate domains and namespaces, this is a finding. \n\nIf namespaces use defaults, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Container namespace access is limited upon runtime execution. Each container is a distinct process so that communication between containers is performed in a manner controlled through security policies that limits the communication so one container cannot modify another container. Different groups of containers with different security needs should be deployed in separate namespaces as a first level of isolation.\n\nNamespaces are a key boundary for network policies, orchestrator access control restrictions, and other important security controls. Separating workloads into namespaces can help contain attacks and limit the impact of mistakes or destructive actions by authorized users.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002530"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"dd00bd4e-c7b5-468e-bb2b-2db40c0dd176","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nRHEL 9 Podman runtime implements unique Linux namespaces, cgroup isolation, and SELinux domains for each container, assigning a separate address space and execution domain per container. Rootless Podman further protects host resources by mapping container root to an unprivileged UID.\nAs verified by lsns and ps -eZ, each container operates independently, satisfying STIG SRG‑APP‑000431‑CTR‑001065 for execution domain isolation.\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233222","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233222","title":"SRG-APP-000435","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233222","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must protect against or limit the effects of all types of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by employing organization-defined security safeguards.","rule_id_src":"SV-233222r961620_rule","rule_id":"SV-233222r961620","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000435-CTR-001070","rule_title":"The container platform must protect against or limit the effects of all types of denial-of-service (DoS) attacks by employing organization-defined security safeguards.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect against or limit the effects of all types of DoS attacks by employing defined security safeguards. Safeguards such as resource limits on memory, storage, and CPU can be used.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform can protect against or limit the effects of all types of DoS attacks by employing defined security safeguards against resource depletion. Examples of resource limits are on memory, storage, and CPU. \n\nIf the container platform cannot be configured to protect against or limit the effects of all types of DoS, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"DoS is a condition when a resource is not available for legitimate users. When this occurs, the organization either cannot accomplish its mission or must operate at degraded capacity.\n\nThis requirement addresses the configuration of the container platform to mitigate the impact of DoS attacks that have occurred. For each container platform component, known and potential DoS attacks must be identified and solutions for each type implemented. A variety of technologies exist to limit or, in some cases, eliminate the effects of DoS attacks (e.g., limiting runtime processes or restricting the number of sessions the container platform runtime open, limiting container resources to memory and CPU).\n\nProcesses are an important indicator of security-and operations-relevant container activity. Process names and their arguments provide important visibility into a container’s activity. If an image includes non-default aliases or renamed binaries, attackers will still attempt to use well-known names.\n\nThe same malicious or unwanted activity might affect multiple deployments across different applications or environments. Staff investigating a potential incident need to find those exposures quickly.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002385"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"1d3bc2af-09e5-48c4-9073-de7781edef99","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":" cat /etc/containers/containers.conf\n[containers]\ndefault_ulimits = [\n  \"nofile=1024:2048\",\n  \"nproc=1024:2048\"\n]\ncpus = 2.0\nmemory = \"4096m\"\npids_limit = 100\n\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman is configured with limits on cpu, memory and process limits."},{"group_id_src":"V-233224","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233224","title":"SRG-APP-000439","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233224","severity":"high","group_title":"The application must protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","rule_id_src":"SV-233224r961632_rule","rule_id":"SV-233224r961632","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000439-CTR-001080","rule_title":"The application must protect the confidentiality and integrity of transmitted information.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to utilize a transmission method that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform configuration to determine if it is using a transmission method that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during transmission.\n\nIf a transmission method is not being used that maintains the confidentiality and integrity of the data, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without protection of the transmitted information, confidentiality and integrity may be compromised since unprotected communications can be intercepted and either read or altered. \r\n\r\nThis requirement applies only to those applications that either are distributed or can allow access to data non-locally. Use of this requirement will be limited to situations where the data owner has a strict requirement for ensuring data integrity and confidentiality is maintained at every step of the data transfer and handling process. When transmitting data, applications need to leverage transmission protection mechanisms, such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec.\r\n\r\nCommunication paths outside the physical protection of a controlled boundary are exposed to the possibility of interception and modification. Protecting the confidentiality and integrity of organizational information can be accomplished by physical means (e.g., employing physical distribution systems) or by logical means (e.g., employing cryptographic techniques). If physical means of protection are employed, then logical means (cryptography) do not have to be employed, and vice versa.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002418"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b4c19069-7af8-4f9d-9d59-ac5ecaf5b282","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"This requirement applies only to those applications that either are distributed or can allow access to data non-locally.\n\ntherefore, since podman is a cli based tool only, this check is not applicable.","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025"},{"group_id_src":"V-233226","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233226","title":"SRG-APP-000441","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233226","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","rule_id_src":"SV-233226r961638_rule","rule_id":"SV-233226r961638","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000441-CTR-001090","rule_title":"The container platform must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation for transmission.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information using mechanisms such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec during preparation for transmission.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the documentation and deployed configuration to determine if the container platform maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during preparation before transmission. \n\nIf the confidentiality and integrity are not maintained using mechanisms such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec during preparation before transmission, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Information may be unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during preparation for transmission within the container platform during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during container image runtime. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information. When transmitting data, the container platform components need to leverage transmission protection mechanisms, such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002420"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"6e5523eb-2b42-44cb-8289-547b48925c5e","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman uses the host tls/ssl settings for outbound connections. the host is FIPS compliant"},{"group_id_src":"V-233227","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233227","title":"SRG-APP-000442","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233227","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","rule_id_src":"SV-233227r961641_rule","rule_id":"SV-233227r961641","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000442-CTR-001095","rule_title":"The container platform must maintain the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to maintain the confidentiality and integrity using mechanisms such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec during reception.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration settings to determine if the container platform maintains the confidentiality and integrity of information during reception.\n\nIf confidentiality and integrity are not maintained using mechanisms such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec during reception, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Information either can be unintentionally or maliciously disclosed or modified during reception for reception within the container platform during aggregation, at protocol transformation points, and during container image runtime. These unauthorized disclosures or modifications compromise the confidentiality or integrity of the information. When receiving data, the container platform components need to leverage protection mechanisms, such as TLS, TLS VPNs, or IPsec.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002422"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"94f29404-c197-4eda-8a5d-876f19fc1f03","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman uses the host tls/ssl settings for outbound connections. the host is FIPS compliant"},{"group_id_src":"V-233228","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233228","title":"SRG-APP-000447","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233228","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must behave in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","rule_id_src":"SV-233228r961656_rule","rule_id":"SV-233228r961656","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000447-CTR-001100","rule_title":"The container platform must behave in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform behave in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the configuration to determine if the container platform behaves in a predictable and documented manner that reflects organizational and system objectives when invalid inputs are received. \n\nIf the container platform does not meet this requirement, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Software or code parameters typically follow well-defined protocols that use structured messages (i.e., commands or queries) to communicate between software modules or system components. Structured messages can contain raw or unstructured data interspersed with metadata or control information. If attacker-supplied inputs to construct structured messages without properly encoding such messages, then the attacker could insert malicious commands or special characters that can cause the data to be interpreted as control information or metadata.\n\nThis requirement guards against adverse or unintended system behavior caused by invalid inputs, where container platform components responses to the invalid input may be disruptive or cause the container image runtime to fail into an unsafe state.\n\nThe behavior will be derived from the organizational and system requirements and includes, but is not limited to, notification of the appropriate personnel, creating an audit record, and rejecting invalid input.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002754"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"ac5b059f-50c5-494e-b543-7a63452ff506","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman itself has predictable outputs for unexpected input\n\nfor example, when incorrect flags are passed\n podman ps -f\nError: flag needs an argument: 'f' in -f\nSee 'podman ps --help'\n"},{"group_id_src":"V-233229","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233229","title":"SRG-APP-000450","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233229","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must implement organization-defined security safeguards to protect system CPU and memory from resource depletion and unauthorized code execution.","rule_id_src":"SV-233229r961665_rule","rule_id":"SV-233229r961665","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000450-CTR-001105","rule_title":"The container platform must implement organization-defined security safeguards to protect system CPU and memory from resource depletion and unauthorized code execution.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to have safeguards in place to protect the system memory and CPU from resource depletion and unauthorized code execution.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine if safeguards are in place to protect the system memory and CPU from resource depletion and unauthorized execution. \n\nIf safeguards are not in place, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The execution of images within the container platform runtime must implement organizational defined security safeguards to prevent distributed denial-of-service (DDOS) and other possible attacks against the container image at runtime.\n\nSecurity safeguards employed to protect memory and CPU include, for example, data execution prevention and address space layout randomization. Data execution prevention safeguards can be software-enforced. Other means of protection are to limit memory and CPU resources to a container.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002824"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"dcccf121-1c69-48d4-8cfe-021f7740969f","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"RHEL 9 hosts implement kernel data execution prevention (NX) and address space layout randomization (ASLR = 2).\nSELinux is set to Enforcing, and Podman uses the default seccomp profile with cgroup‑based CPU and memory limitations defined in /etc/containers/containers.conf.\nContainers run in rootless mode under these enforced safeguards, effectively protecting system CPU and memory from resource depletion and unauthorized code execution.","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nthe host has limits in place along with configuration limits for podman"},{"group_id_src":"V-233230","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233230","title":"SRG-APP-000454","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233230","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must remove old components after updated versions have been installed.","rule_id_src":"SV-233230r961677_rule","rule_id":"SV-233230r961677","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000454-CTR-001110","rule_title":"The container platform must remove old components after updated versions have been installed.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform registry to update organization-defined images with current approved vendor version and remove obsolete images after updated versions have been installed. Configure the container platform runtime to execute latest organization-defined images from the container platform registry.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform registry documentation and configuration to determine if organization-defined images contains latest approved vendor software image version. \n\nIf organization-defined images do not contain the latest approved vendor software image version, this is a finding. \n\nReview container platform registry documentation and configuration to determine if organization-defined images are removed after updated versions have been installed. \n\nIf organization-defined images are not removed after updated versions have been installed, this is a finding. \n\nReview container platform runtime documentation and configuration to determine if organization-define images are executing latest image version from the container platform registry. \n\nIf container platform runtime is not executing latest organization-defined images from the container platform registry, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Previous versions of container platform components that are not removed from the container platform after updates have been installed may be exploited by adversaries by causing older components to execute which contain vulnerabilities. When these components are deleted, the likelihood of this happening is removed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002617"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"1292073c-d307-408b-9067-450fc1c23836","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not provide container registries functions locally. However, upstream container images are updated regularly as result of monthly security scans and the programs normal patching cycle. "},{"group_id_src":"V-233231","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233231","title":"SRG-APP-000454","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233231","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform registry must remove old container images after updating versions have been made available.","rule_id_src":"SV-233231r961677_rule","rule_id":"SV-233231r961677","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000454-CTR-001115","rule_title":"The container platform registry must remove old container images after updating versions have been made available.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform registry to update organization-defined images with current approved vendor version and remove obsolete images after updated versions have been installed. Configure the container platform runtime to execute latest organization-defined images from the container platform registry.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform registry documentation and configuration to determine if organization-defined images contains latest approved vendor software image version. \n\nIf organization-defined images do not contain the latest approved vendor software image version, this is a finding. \n\nReview container platform registry documentation and configuration to determine if organization-defined images are removed after updated versions have been installed. \n\nIf organization-defined images are not removed after updated versions have been installed, this is a finding. \n\nReview container platform runtime documentation and configuration to determine if organization-defined images are executing latest image version from the container registry. \n\nIf container platform runtime is not executing latest organization-defined images from the container platform registry, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Obsolete and stale images need to be removed from the registry to ensure the container platform maintains a secure posture. While the storing of these images does not directly pose a threat, they do increase the likelihood of these images being deployed. Removing stale or obsolete images and only keeping the most recent versions of those that are still in use removes any possibility of vulnerable images being deployed.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002617"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"e7ec5967-bef8-40d1-be1e-1b321404a442","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not provide container registries functions locally. However, upstream container images are updated regularly as result of monthly security scans and the programs normal patching cycle."},{"group_id_src":"V-233233","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233233","title":"SRG-APP-000456","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233233","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform registry must contain the latest images with most recent updates and execute within the container platform runtime as authorized by IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, and STIGs. ","rule_id_src":"SV-233233r961683_rule","rule_id":"SV-233233r961683","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000456-CTR-001125","rule_title":"The container platform registry must contain the latest images with most recent updates and execute within the container platform runtime as authorized by IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, and STIGs. ","fix_text":"Configure the container platform registry to use approved vendor repository to ensure latest images containing security-relevant updates are installed.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform registry inspects and contains approved vendor repository latest images containing security-relevant updates within a timeframe directed by an authoritative source (IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs, etc.). \n\nIf the container platform registry does not contain the latest image with security-relevant updates within the time period directed by the authoritative source, this is a finding.\n\nThe container platform registry should help the user understand where the code in the environment was deployed from, and must provide controls that prevent deployment from untrusted sources or registries.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Software supporting the container platform, images in the registry must stay up to date with the latest patches, service packs, and hot fixes. Not updating the container platform and container images will expose the organization to vulnerabilities.\n\nFlaws discovered during security assessments, continuous monitoring, incident response activities, or information system error handling must also be addressed expeditiously.\n\nOrganization-defined time periods for updating security-relevant container platform components may vary based on a variety of factors including, for example, the security category of the information system or the criticality of the update (i.e., severity of the vulnerability related to the discovered flaw).\n\nThis requirement will apply to software patch management solutions that are used to install patches across the enclave and to applications themselves that are not part of that patch management solution. For example, many browsers today provide the capability to install their own patch software. Patch criticality, as well as system criticality will vary. Therefore, the tactical situations regarding the patch management process will also vary. This means that the time period utilized must be a configurable parameter. Time frames for application of security-relevant software updates may be dependent upon the Information Assurance Vulnerability Management (IAVM) process.\n\nThe container platform components will be configured to check for and install security-relevant software updates within an identified time period from the availability of the update. The container platform registry will ensure the images are current. The specific time period will be defined by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, and STIGs).","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002605"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"24c331e3-c877-47e4-af7c-4e2fcadadf40","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not provide container registries functions locally. However, upstream container images are updated regularly as result of monthly security scans and the programs normal patching cycle."},{"group_id_src":"V-233234","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233234","title":"SRG-APP-000456","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233234","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform runtime must have updates installed within the time period directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, and STIGs).","rule_id_src":"SV-233234r961683_rule","rule_id":"SV-233234r961683","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000456-CTR-001130","rule_title":"The container platform runtime must have updates installed within the time period directed by an authoritative source (e.g., IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, and STIGs).","fix_text":"Configure the container platform registry to use approved vendor repository to ensure latest images containing security-relevant updates are installed within the time period directed by the authoritative source.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review documentation and configuration to determine if the container platform registry inspects and contains approved vendor repository latest images containing security-relevant updates within a timeframe directed by an authoritative source (IAVM, CTOs, DTMs, STIGs, etc.). \n\nIf the container platform registry does not contain the latest image with security-relevant updates within the time period directed by the authoritative source, this is a finding.\n\nThe container platform registry should help the user understand where the code in the environment was deployed from and must provide controls that prevent deployment from untrusted sources or registries.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform runtime must be carefully monitored for vulnerabilities, and when problems are detected, they must be remediated quickly. A vulnerable runtime exposes all containers it supports, as well as the host itself, to potentially significant risk. Organizations should use tools to look for Common Vulnerabilities and Exposures (CVEs) vulnerabilities in the runtimes deployed, to upgrade any instances at risk, and to ensure that orchestrators only allow deployments to properly maintained runtimes.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002605"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"70c60f75-4438-40b0-ae28-b4986f48c9ec","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman and its components are updated in defined intervals determined by security scanning and update cycles of the program. usually monthly is the target for system updates. "},{"group_id_src":"V-233242","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233242","title":"SRG-APP-000472","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233242","severity":"medium","group_title":"The organization-defined role must verify correct operation of security functions in the container platform.","rule_id_src":"SV-233242r961731_rule","rule_id":"SV-233242r961731","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000472-CTR-001170","rule_title":"The organization-defined role must verify correct operation of security functions in the container platform.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform configuration and installation settings to perform verification of the correct operation of security functions.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation and configuration verification of the correct operation of security functions, which may include the valid connection to an external security manager (ESM). \n\nIf verification of the correct operation of security functions is not performed, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without verification, security functions may not operate correctly and this failure may go unnoticed within the container platform. The container platform components must identity and ensure the security functions are still operational and applicable to the organization.\n\nSecurity functions are responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nNotifications provided by information systems include, for example, electronic alerts to system administrators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002696"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5929cc44-c3ae-4555-a389-f11859200f40","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is beyond the scope of the podman program. however this type of logging is performed by the host the software is installed on. Therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233243","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233243","title":"SRG-APP-000473","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233243","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must perform verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.","rule_id_src":"SV-233243r961734_rule","rule_id":"SV-233243r961734","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000473-CTR-001175","rule_title":"The container platform must perform verification of the correct operation of security functions: upon system startup and/or restart; upon command by a user with privileged access; and/or every 30 days. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to perform verification of the correct operation of security functions, which may include the connection validation, upon product startup/restart, or by a user with privileged access, and/or every 30 days.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform documentation.\n\nVerify that the container platform is configured to perform verification of the correct operation of security functions, which may include the valid connection to an external security manager (ESM), upon product startup/restart, by a user with privileged access, and/or every 30 days.\n\nIf it is not, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Without verification, security functions may not operate correctly and this failure may go unnoticed within the container platform.\r\n\r\nSecurity functions are responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\r\n\r\nNotifications provided by information systems include, for example, electronic alerts to organization-defined role.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002699"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"bdcd0804-51ee-459c-90e8-1019d3311eb9","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nbbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is beyond the scope of the podman program. however this type of logging is performed by the host the software is installed on. Therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233244","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233244","title":"SRG-APP-000474","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233244","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide system notifications to the system administrator and operational staff when anomalies in the operation of the organization-defined security functions are discovered.","rule_id_src":"SV-233244r961737_rule","rule_id":"SV-233244r961737","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000474-CTR-001180","rule_title":"The container platform must provide system notifications to the system administrator and operational staff when anomalies in the operation of the organization-defined security functions are discovered.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform runtime to notify system administrator and operation staff when anomalies in the operation of the security functions as defined in site security plan are discovered.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review container platform runtime documentation and configuration settings. \n\nIf the container platform is not configured to notify organization-defined information system role when anomalies in the operation of security functions as defined by site security plan are discovered, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"If anomalies are not acted upon, security functions may fail to secure the container within the container platform runtime.\n\nSecurity functions are responsible for enforcing the system security policy and supporting the isolation of code and data on which the protection is based. Security functionality includes, but is not limited to, establishing system accounts, configuring access authorizations (i.e., permissions, privileges), setting events to be audited, and setting intrusion detection parameters.\n\nNotifications provided by information systems include, for example, electronic alerts to system administrators.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-002702"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"0808b894-6a5f-43c0-8740-d0eba12fd564","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is beyond the scope of the podman program. however this type of logging is performed by the host the software is installed on. Therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233252","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233252","title":"SRG-APP-000492","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233252","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-233252r961791_rule","rule_id":"SV-233252r961791","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000492-CTR-001220","rule_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to verify audit records are generated on successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security objects. \n\nIf audit records are not generated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"The container platform and its components must generate audit records when successful and unsuccessful access security objects occur. All the components must use the same standard so that the events can be tied together to understand what took place within the overall container platform. This must establish, correlate, and help assist with investigating the events relating to an incident, or identify those responsible.\n\nWithout audit record generation access controls levels can access by unauthorized users unknowingly for malicious intent creating vulnerabilities within the container platform.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"44ff2ee0-1ee1-4a45-885e-cfadc4511dc4","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is beyond the scope of the podman program. however this type of logging is performed by the host the software is installed on. Therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233253","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233253","title":"SRG-APP-000493","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233253","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-233253r961794_rule","rule_id":"SV-233253r961794","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000493-CTR-001225","rule_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels occur.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to verify audit records are generated on successful/unsuccessful attempts to access security levels. \n\nIf audit records are not generated, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Unauthorized users could access the security levels to exploit vulnerabilities within the container platform component. All the components must use the same standard so that the events can be tied together to understand what took place within the overall container platform. This must establish, correlate, and help assist with investigating the events relating to an incident, or identify those responsible.\n\nWithout audit record generation, unauthorized users can access security levels unknowingly for malicious intent creating vulnerabilities within the container platform.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-000172"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"7e2dc651-153c-43c7-b412-70fb492122ab","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nThis is beyond the scope of the podman program. however this type of logging is performed by the host the software is installed on. Therefore not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-233254","group_tree":[{"id":"V-233254","title":"SRG-APP-000494","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-233254","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must generate audit records when successful/unsuccessful attempts to access categories of information (e.g., classification levels) occur.","rule_id_src":"SV-233254r961797_rule","rule_id":"SV-233254r961797","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000494-CTR-