he system by logically separated communications paths.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to protect nonlocal maintenance sessions by separating the maintenance session from other network sessions with the system by logically separated communications paths.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the container platform is configured to protect nonlocal maintenance sessions by separating the maintenance session from other network sessions with the system by logically separated communications paths.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to protect nonlocal maintenance sessions by separating the maintenance session from other network sessions with the system by logically separated communications paths, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Nonlocal maintenance and diagnostic activities are conducted by individuals who communicate through either an external or internal network.\nCommunications paths can be logically separated using encryption.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004192"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"37a30568-f609-4fbb-a1ad-1f4a8d87b188","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\npodman does not have any kind of listeners for communications like maintenance vs any other kind of traffic. Therefore it cannot separate the two, because neither exist. this is not applicable."},{"group_id_src":"V-263599","group_tree":[{"id":"V-263599","title":"SRG-APP-000910","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-263599","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","rule_id_src":"SV-263599r982473_rule","rule_id":"SV-263599r982473","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000910-CTR-000300","rule_title":"The container platform must include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the container platform is configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to include only approved trust anchors in trust stores or certificate stores managed by the organization, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Public key infrastructure (PKI) certificates are certificates with visibility external to organizational systems and certificates related to the internal operations of systems, such as application-specific time services. In cryptographic systems with a hierarchical structure, a trust anchor is an authoritative source (i.e., a certificate authority) for which trust is assumed and not derived. A root certificate for a PKI system is an example of a trust anchor. A trust store or certificate store maintains a list of trusted root certificates.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004909"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"59302483-39ea-43f0-9277-36140fd4a747","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman uses the hosts ssl configurations, which are setup for include only trusted anchors and ca certs."},{"group_id_src":"V-263600","group_tree":[{"id":"V-263600","title":"SRG-APP-000915","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-263600","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","rule_id_src":"SV-263600r982475_rule","rule_id":"SV-263600r982475","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000915-CTR-000310","rule_title":"The container platform must provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the container platform is configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to provide protected storage for cryptographic keys with organization-defined safeguards and/or hardware protected key store, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"A Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an example of a hardware-protected data store that can be used to protect cryptographic keys.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004910"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"b1fa0e95-71e5-48e7-a67d-94153e68425c","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not interact with keystore data, as it runs as a user process. Therefore this is not applicable"},{"group_id_src":"V-263601","group_tree":[{"id":"V-263601","title":"SRG-APP-000920","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-263601","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container platform must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","rule_id_src":"SV-263601r982477_rule","rule_id":"SV-263601r982477","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000920-CTR-000320","rule_title":"The container platform must synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Verify the container platform is configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components.\n\nIf the container platform is not configured to synchronize system clocks within and between systems or system components, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Time synchronization of system clocks is essential for the correct execution of many system services, including identification and authentication processes that involve certificates and time-of-day restrictions as part of access control. Denial of service or failure to deny expired credentials may result without properly synchronized clocks within and between systems and system components. Time is commonly expressed in Coordinated Universal Time (UTC), a modern continuation of Greenwich Mean Time (GMT), or local time with an offset from UTC. The granularity of time measurements refers to the degree of synchronization between system clocks and reference clocks, such as clocks synchronizing within hundreds of milliseconds or tens of milliseconds. Organizations may define different time granularities for system components. Time service can be critical to other security capabilities such as access control and identification and authentication depending on the nature of the mechanisms used to support the capabilities.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-004922"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"5b09c705-d64c-45d5-856d-adff45a57315","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":"","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nPodman does not use internal clocking. it uses the host kernels clock time. Therefore this is not a finding"},{"group_id_src":"V-270875","group_tree":[{"id":"V-270875","title":"SRG-APP-000247","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-270875","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container must have resource request limits set.","rule_id_src":"SV-270875r1050646_rule","rule_id":"SV-270875r1050646","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000247-CTR-000330","rule_title":"The container must have resource request limits set.","fix_text":"Configure the container platform to restrict the ability of users or other systems to launch denial-of-service (DoS) attacks from the container platform components by setting resource limits on resources such as memory, storage, and CPU utilization.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine that resource limits are set.\n\nIf the container platform does not enforce resource limits, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Setting a container resource request limit allows the container platform to determine the best location for the container to execute. The container platform looks at the resources available and finds the location that will require the minimum resources for the container to execute. Examples of resources that can be specified are CPU, memory, and storage.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001095"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"10642955-bb3d-4ca7-8b3b-87e00a1308d5","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_a_finding","overrides":{},"comments":" cat /etc/containers/containers.conf\n[containers]\ndefault_ulimits = [\n  \"nofile=1024:2048\",\n  \"nproc=1024:2048\"\n]\ncpus = 2.0\nmemory = \"4096m\"\npids_limit = 100\n\n[admin@mirhel9 ~]$\n","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\nlimits are set"},{"group_id_src":"V-270876","group_tree":[{"id":"V-270876","title":"SRG-APP-000380","description":"<GroupDescription></GroupDescription>"}],"group_id":"V-270876","severity":"medium","group_title":"The container root filesystem must be mounted as read-only.","rule_id_src":"SV-270876r1050649_rule","rule_id":"SV-270876r1050649","rule_version":"SRG-APP-000380-CTR-000340","rule_title":"The container root filesystem must be mounted as read-only.","fix_text":"Review and remove nonsystem containers previously created with read-write permissions. Configure the container platform to force the root filesystem to be mounted as read-only.","weight":"10.0","check_content":"Review the container platform configuration to determine that the root filesystem is mounted as read-only.\n\nIf the container platform does not enforce such access restrictions, this is a finding.","check_content_ref":{"href":"Container_Platform__SRG.xml","name":"M"},"classification":"Unclassified","discussion":"Any changes to a container must be made by rebuilding the image and redeploying the new container image. Once a container is running, changes to the root filesystem should not be needed, thus preserving the immutable nature of the container. Any attempts to change the root filesystem are usually malicious in nature and can be prevented by making the root filesystem read-only.","false_positives":"","false_negatives":"","documentable":"false","security_override_guidance":"","potential_impacts":"","third_party_tools":"","ia_controls":"","responsibility":"","mitigations":"","mitigation_control":"","legacy_ids":[],"ccis":["CCI-001813"],"reference_identifier":"5239","uuid":"80df49c4-ae00-4c7d-ba1f-c4ee941de758","stig_uuid":"9c902529-7478-4e25-82fb-3d49f4b7d7d4","status":"not_applicable","overrides":{},"comments":"podman containers are rootless. meaning their storage, and runtime are run as the user that owns them. Therefore a requirement of making the container rootfs be read only is futile, since the user has enough permissions inherently to modify the container. This check should be not applicable.","finding_details":"bbowen 11-20-2025\n\npodman does not allow other users to run containers not owned by the same user."}]}],"active":false,"mode":2,"has_path":true,"target_data":{"target_type":"Computing","host_name":"msn_srvr","ip_address":"","mac_address":"","fqdn":"","comments":"","role":"Workstation","is_web_database":false,"technology_area":"None","web_db_site":"","web_db_instance":"","classification":"Unclassified"},"cklb_version":"1.0"}